project, so add it to the list as well.

commit_message:
Fix retrieve_auth_url in case Keystone URL does not contain port.

Sahara calls retrieve_auth_url() to retrieve auth_url from input
uri. However, this function does not work correctly if input uri
does not contain port.

Change-Id: Ic7a65cd36a237d68151936404567c3bd7d068117
Closes-Bug: #1473434
(cherry picked from commit 710ee9b8ad655d70aa70f3ace2a4e81ea8513b33)

commit_message:
Replace dict.iteritems() with dict.items() in bin directory of swift.

The iteritems() of Python 2 dictionaries has been renamed to items() on
Python 3.

Change-Id: I4bdc064c90bab56cd60f2dca2a5a78426ffbb31c

commit_message:
Make logic of unit tests responsive to the method names

The two methods, test_authorize_succeeds_for_tenant_name_in_roles and
test_authorize_succeeds_for_tenant_id_in_roles, have names that don't
match what they are testing. tenant_name and tenant_id need to be
switched.

Change-Id: I7cb0a7d2b2111127fd5d6b55f2da6a3eadf2235d

commit_message:
Keystone: do not allow specifying service names

This fixes service cleanup. Keystone resources are only cleaned up if
they have the correct magic prefix, but services were not reliably
created with that prefix.

This also adds some logging that made it easier to discover this
issue, and fixes a few minor typos.

Closes-Bug: #1474322
Change-Id: Ic58271bbc9a84feff4f60229a66e0ca00834a79c

commit_message:
Fix chainloading iPXE (undionly.kpxe)

This patch is making the neutron DHCP provider to explicitly check if
the request is coming from iPXE before ACK'ing the PXE request with the
iPXE script (When iPXE is enabled only).

Also, update the documentation that explains how to configure neutron
for iPXE to create the "ipxe" tag based on the DHCP user class or DHCP
option 175 (as before).

Conflicts:
	doc/source/deploy/install-guide.rst

Change-Id: I60f9f515a9bd45aed6b2f6f9165a2f85259b3879
Closes-Bug: #1454332
(cherry picked from commit 4ec47b66602b4eb0b86ffd1fd69b70ef2bf16a25)

commit_message:
Remove osclients from runner and scenario signature

* Remove from base.Scenario clients and admin_clients
  arguments. In future we will create OpenStackScenario
  subclass that will contain this logic
* Fully remove usage of osclients from runner
* Fix related unit tests

Change-Id: I0769a10bf55ff7440ef46643dbcc8005cdb7523e

commit_message:
AggregateTypeAffinityFilter multi values

Add AggregateTypeAffinityFilter multi values support
The value of the instance_type metadata entry is
a string that may contain either a single instance_type name or a comma
separated list of instance_type names. e.g. 'm1.nano' or "m1.nano,m1.small"

Change-Id: Ie2298c32d0fb53ba7195d2e276c6f2c1e7704739
Closes-Bug: 1463773

commit_message:
Add support for forcing migrate_flavor_data

In some cases it might be helpful to force the migration of flavor
data. For example, when operating on a snapshot of a production
database there may be instances in an operating state that would
stop the migration from finishing. Blocking on this will make it
impossible to finish the migrations (once the migrations require
all the data has been migrated).

Change-Id: I4f6c0679b144897f2bfc2fa06bc7c72b25a85fd3
(cherry picked from commit 5f515dda64de7047fbb2fe5c4076874d1f2aa175)

2015-07-10 14:32:17.314 |   File "/home/jenkins/workspace/gate-heat-templates-python26/.tox/py26/lib/python2.6/site-packages/mock/mock.py", line 132

commit_message:
Make heat-templates CI passable again - remove py26 job

Python 2.6 CI of heat-templates broke down with new release of mock:

2015-07-10 14:32:17.314 |   File "/home/jenkins/workspace/gate-heat-templates-python26/.tox/py26/lib/python2.6/site-packages/mock/mock.py", line 132
2015-07-10 14:32:17.315 |     _builtins = {name for name in dir(builtins) if not name.startswith('_')}

The Python 2.6 testing has been deprecated for some time [1], so this
commit removes it from heat-templates to make the CI passable again.

[1] http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2014-November/051551.html

Change-Id: I4fe77a6c10b41644e131cde70534abf992a6f3b3
Closes-Bug: #1473967

commit_message:
Wait server to be terminated in VolumesV2NegativeTest.

In some cases, it takes some time to delete server. This might
cause the tear down class fail to delete other resource. Wait
the server to be terminated in test case can avoid this failure.

Change-Id: I10e87cf792f90edc2b5db208205c7425f1a6cec5
Closes-Bug: #1471712

commit_message:
Use openstack cli for cinder type creation

This command was commented out so assumedly there used to be a bug. Switch to
OpenStackClient as the cinder CLI doesn't handle v3 auth correctly.

Implements: bp keystonev3
Change-Id: I1acdc04cf04b7056701bdded31ef2a015de5bce3

commit_message:
Use Keystone V3 API for role creation

Always use the V3 API for role creation.

Groups only exist in the v3 identity API and so we must specify
--os-identity-api-version in these commands.

Implements: bp keystonev3
Closes-Bug: #1470668
Change-Id: I5e01d23ebcb5a0c7de56233071a4eb9b16d3b813

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-07-03 01:21:42.000000000', 'message': 'Move signals to SignalResponder class

This change relocates the code that creates and deletes heat, swift and
zaqar signals out of SoftwareDeployment and into SignalResponder, as a
first step in making these signals available to all resources. As part of
this change the structure of the Swift URLs was changed to match that of
the SwiftSignal resource.

commit_message:
Move signals to SignalResponder class

This change relocates the code that creates and deletes heat, swift and
zaqar signals out of SoftwareDeployment and into SignalResponder, as a
first step in making these signals available to all resources. As part of
this change the structure of the Swift URLs was changed to match that of
the SwiftSignal resource.

Change-Id: Id5701b3696b0ab41433a3f158fabce1f36aabe16
Implements: blueprint uniform-resource-signals

'}, {'created': '2015-02-25 05:49:06.000000000', 'message': 'Remove db layer hard-code permission checks for v2.1 QuotaSets/QuotaClassSets

This patch removes db layer hard-code permission checks for v2.1
QuotaSets/QuotaSetClass API.

For back-compatibility, this patch add hard-code permission checks in REST API
layer for v2 API.

For QuotaClassSets, because the index and update method with different permission,
so this patch adds new policy rule for each action instead of extension level policy
rule.

This patch also correct the unittest for quota/quota-classes. It ensure v2.1
unittest use normal user context for all the tests that ensure the v2.1 code is
un-winded by any other permission checks except policy rules.

Partially implements bp v3-api-policy
DocImpact

Change-Id: I0a70c092d572d0989dd6fd7f873638a9570817b7
'}, {'created': '2015-02-25 08:02:45.000000000', 'message': 'Remove db layer hard-code permission checks for v2.1 QuotaSets/QuotaClassSets

This patch removes db layer hard-code permission checks for v2.1
QuotaSets/QuotaSetClass API.

For back-compatibility, this patch add hard-code permission checks in REST API
layer for v2 API.

For QuotaClassSets, because the index and update method with different permission,
so this patch adds new policy rule for each action instead of extension level policy
rule.

This patch also correct the unittest for quota/quota-classes. It ensure v2.1
unittest use normal user context for all the tests that ensure the v2.1 code is
un-winded by any other permission checks except policy rules.

Partially implements bp v3-api-policy
DocImpact

Change-Id: I0a70c092d572d0989dd6fd7f873638a9570817b7
'}, {'created': '2015-02-26 04:56:12.000000000', 'message': 'Remove db layer hard-code permission checks for v2.1 QuotaSets/QuotaClassSets

This patch removes db layer hard-code permission checks for v2.1
QuotaSets/QuotaSetClass API.

For back-compatibility, this patch add hard-code permission checks in REST API
layer for v2 API.

For QuotaClassSets, because the index and update method with different permission,
so this patch adds new policy rule for each action instead of extension level policy
rule.

For QuotaSets, because the show and defaults method with different permission,
so this patch adds separated rule for defaults method.

This patch also correct the unittest for quota/quota-classes. It ensure v2.1
unittest use normal user context for all the tests that ensure the v2.1 code is
un-winded by any other permission checks except policy rules.

Partially implements bp v3-api-policy
DocImpact

Change-Id: I0a70c092d572d0989dd6fd7f873638a9570817b7

commit_message:
Cleanup quota_class unittest with appropriate request context

For v2.1 quota_class API, all the hard-code permission was deleted.
The quota_class code is un-winded except the policy enforcement at
REST API entrance.

This patch adjusts the request context in the unittest, use non-admin
context for all the v2.1 unittest.

Partially implements bp nova-api-policy-final-part

Change-Id: I0a70c092d572d0989dd6fd7f873638a9570817b7

subject: Remove db layer hard-code permission checks for quota_class_create/update

commit_message:
Remove db layer hard-code permission checks for quota_class_create/update

This patch removes db layer hard-code permission checks for
quota_class_create/update.

For v2 API, this patch adds back-comptiable permission checks at REST
API layer.

For v2.1 API, this patch adds new rule for update method.

Partially implements bp nova-api-policy-final-part

SecurityImpact
UpgradeImpact: Due to the db layer permission checks deleted, the policy
rule "os_compute_api:os-quota-class-sets:update" was updated with
a default that match the permission as before. Admin should be notified
to update their policy configuration to keep permission as before.

Change-Id: Icddc7e5cc1c11ab3d272f61a2ef623d3f750030c

commit_message:
Add python-openstackclient to global-requirements

Clients for newer projects are being built as plugins to
python-openstackclient.  These clients have an explicit
dependency on python-openstackclient for them to be meaningful.

Examples:
 https://github.com/stackforge/python-cueclient
 https://github.com/stackforge/python-congressclient

Change-Id: Ic48d1db4343de6c815790b5eba00fe32e2fd4f2b

commit_message:
Add documentation for Xen via libvirt to config-reference

To do this I had do some changes to existing Xen documentation:

Apply minimal changes to filenames, enabling later addition of
hypervisor support using Xen+libvirt, renaming XenServer files
using git mv
- section_introduction-to-xen.xml > section_hypervisor_xen_xapi.xml
- section_xen-install.xml > section_xapi-install.xml
- section_compute-configure-xen.xml > section_compute-configure-xapi.xml

All XenServer docs can now be identified using xapi in the filename.

Renamed relevant occurances of Xen to XenServer in XenServer docs and
the Hypervisor page and replaced outdated references to Xen.org with
XenProject.org

Changed URL from introduction-to-xen.html to xen_libvirt.html in
doc/common/section_kvm_enable.xml (did not include references in .po
and .pot files in locale, which are autogenerated)

All of the new Xen via Libvirt documentation is in a new page called
section_hypervisor_xen_libvirt.html

Change-Id: I6a6de021ef4e5de4fe28aa971411e07b656c969c
Closes-Bug: #1253565
Signed-off-by: Lars Kurth <lars.kurth@xenproject.org>
Co-Authored-By: Jim Fehlig <jfehlig@suse.com>
Co-Authored-By: Anthony Perard <anthony.perard@citrix.com>

commit_message:
[network-guide] Update provider OVS scenario

Update provider networks with Open vSwitch scenario as
follows:

1) Remove extraneous configuration from neutron and ML2
   configuration on compute nodes.
2) Fix various conventions issues.
3) Generally improve wording and diagrams.

Patch also includes minor fixes to the Linux bridge scenario.

Change-Id: Ie0e32eafdc4eedd67f4c95400faf9f73bc1f844b
Partial-Bug: #1465778
Partial-Bug: #1465783

commit_message:
Moving out the cisco n1kv section to stackforge

Since most of the n1kv plugin code resides in stackforge/networking-cisco
repo, it's best to move the n1kv section there

Change-Id: Ic1388980dea0d27dfa5e84869f1f20cc9bff78e5
Closes-Bug: #1441400
(cherry picked from commit c34ce7c9845cc56f981e0ee8714d1f9345df5852)

commit_message:
Ensure the the setup.cfg version has an epoch set

Since the versions have all just gotten much smaller due
to the new release scheme we should really be cautious
about this and ensure we correctly set the epoch so that
people that actually use cinder install it correctly after
the version change.

Change-Id: Ib3637a640b63e5f4380224c847a03e4d12289d37

Looks fine to me, but makes me wonder why the restriction was there in the first place. I would feel more comfortable seeing some output from a volume with snapshots being successfully extended, or some type of confirmation that this was an unnecessary restriction.'}, {'account_id': 7350, 'date': '2015-07-05 17:32:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I successfully tested "volume extend" on a volume with snapshots (with a different driver than glusterfs, but the code path was the same (RemoteFS)).'}, {'account_id': 4523, 'date': '2015-07-07 19:17:54.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

The restriction was there in the first place for GlusterFS just for simplicity.

But, it looks like there may be another reason to restrict this.

If you resize the volume, you have a mismatch between volume['size'], and snapshot['volume_size'] in the database since snapshot['volume_size'] is not ever updated that I can see.

snapshot['volume_size'] is then used in quota calculations, so this seems like it will lead to bad behavior.

This may be broken for drivers that are currently allowing this, unless I'm missing something."}, {'account_id': 11904, 'date': '2015-07-07 19:30:29.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Does it matter if volume size is different than snapshot size? I would think that is expected behavior.

At least with our storage you can have snapshots on a volume and extend that volume. The snapshot's size is still the pre-extended size. I would think that correct then that the cinder DB would have different sizes for the two."}, {'account_id': 4523, 'date': '2015-07-07 20:02:39.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

My concern isn't about snapshot vs volume size, it's about two different representations of volume size: snapshot['volume_size'] vs volume['size']

What does it mean when those differ?"}, {'account_id': 14428, 'date': '2015-07-08 07:15:55.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

@Eric,

I think snapshot should still maintain the pre-extended size of volume (volume_size) though it is not equal to volume['size'].

When we create a volume from snapshot, size of the newly created volume should be snapshot['volume_size'] but not volume['size'].
For that we need to maintain snapshot['volume_size']."}, {'account_id': 7350, 'date': '2015-07-08 08:16:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I also think that snapshot['volume_size'] vs volume['size'] could be different. Let's consider this scenario:

1) I create a volume of 10G and make a snapshot of this volume

2) I extend this volume to 1T

If, during the volume extend, we also increase snapshot['volume_size'] to 1T, it means we won't be able to: cinder create --snapshot-id $snap 20G because Cinder will complain 'volume size must be >= 1T'

But I see no reason why we couldn't create a volume of 20G from a snapshot of a volume that "used to be" 10G.

My other concern is: why should GlusterFS (or all RemoteFS) driver not support this whilst the other drivers support this. I mean, if (**if**) there's a bug, why should only the GlusterFS driver be affected ?'}, {'account_id': 10796, 'date': '2015-07-09 08:35:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

@Eric,
  Its not clear from your comment how snapshot['volume_size']
can lead to bad behaviour ? Can you provide an example of
this to understand better ? I also couldn't find where
snapshot['volume_size'] gets used in quota calculation."}, {'account_id': 4523, 'date': '2015-07-09 14:36:01.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2

After poking at this a bit, I'm fairly convinced this is ok.  I just had no idea this behavior existed and wasn't sure it added up.  Thanks for the comments."}, {'account_id': 11904, 'date': '2015-07-09 14:37:59.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Workflow+1

OK, Eric is happy, so that's good enough for me. Code-wise everything looks good, so this looks fine."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-07-09 14:38:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Verified

Starting gate jobs.
http://status.openstack.org/zuul/'}, {'account_id': 9535, 'date': '2015-07-09 14:49:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

Not even a test to confirm that the code can now extend with snapshots and that there are no regressions later? :-(

@Sean, was your intention to +1 and +1 Workflow?  Or did you mean to +2 and +1 Workflow?'}, {'account_id': 14428, 'date': '2015-07-09 15:04:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Thanks everyone.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-07-09 15:58:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+2

commit_message:
GlusterFS: support extending a volume that has snapshots

GlusterFS driver currently prevents extending a volume that has
snapshots. This patch enables this feature to GlusterFS driver.

Closes-Bug: #1470148
Change-Id: I763b1a84f32277f3efab2382ad144768bee59aa6

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-07-12 12:48:48.000000000', 'message': 'Consider h/c /var/tmp & /dev/shm as potential

Previously general_hardcoded_tmp plugin was only testing
for hard-coded usage of "/tmp/", however the same issues
can be present on other FHS locations such as /var/tmp/
and /dev/shm.

This change adds these additional locations for
consideration.

commit_message:
Consider other hardcoded tmp paths

Previously general_hardcoded_tmp plugin was only testing
for hard-coded usage of "/tmp/", however the same issues
can be present on other FHS locations such as /var/tmp/
and /dev/shm.

This change adds these additional locations for
consideration.

Closes-Bug: #1473725
Signed-off-by: Dave Walker (Daviey) <email@daviey.com>
Change-Id: I76f154134e6cc90a1f30c1c5e41c98dd74c13d33

commit_message:
Fix symlinks to config-{internal,external}.sh

Many of these were actually files containing the path to the real
script, instead of being symlinks.

config-{internal,external}.sh files in openvswitch/ovs-base were not
needed and were thus deleted.

Also update minimal-environment-vars.md after symlinks were fixed.

Change-Id: I11c3e735067b1feb83c3184c32333e598fbdf590
Closes-Bug: #1474227

commit_message:
Fixes login failure to Horizon dashboard

This is a temporary workaround to fix a Django error preventing
the Kolla Horizon login, while waiting for a fix upstream.
It is part of a patch created by Matthias Runge <mrunge@redhat.com>
https://review.openstack.org/gitweb?p=openstack%2Fdjango_openstack_auth.git;a=commitdiff;h=adfc494ec17ee43847d7c0c833dad9c178f29358

I've just used the patch for openstack_auth/user.py

Change-Id: I2c2ad0042f9c60a839d8ee9bca904465bee9361f
Closes-bug: #1469284

commit_message:
Switch all uses of json to oslo_serialization

This commit migrates all the usage of the json library to use jsonutils
from oslo_serialization. On python 3 httplib2 returns a bytes type for
the response body however all the methods in the json library are
expecting str types. We could switch all the uses of json.loads to
encode the input prior to calling json.loads however oslo_serialization
has baked in all dual python version edge conditions around this into
a call compatible lib which is much cleaner.

Change-Id: Icee30fb74db128c77b2c0c27e68b5801bd138cd5

commit_message:
Make ceilometer run with mod_wsgi by default

Ceilometer will now use the ENABLE_HTTPD_MOD_WSGI_SERVICES value
to set the default value for CEILOMETER_USE_MOD_WSGI, meaning that
by default the ceilometer api service will run under mod_wsgi.
This is now the recommended mode for deployments.

Depends-On: I2d81f25522ad982657d7f4239bfe66bfb5538295
Depends-On: Ib38177125ddc8e97e74237e9242e2ea09cff28d4
Depends-On: I9e5e792ef43f9a3cdc0b84c73f27b62109ed5d31
Change-Id: I61fcc84d1f841d6ede1539dc4e3bdae5aecc02de

commit_message:
N1Kv:Adding params for IPv6 communication with VSM

Adding ability to configure IPv6 control address of VSM,
in the n1kv.conf file, to enable N1kv VEM to talk to VSM
over IPv6

Change-Id: Iac92569ec19a879091111f78474aebb83292999d
(cherry picked from commit bfb33bfe31111f4fe38226131ee0a284e7f1ef29)

'}, {'created': '2015-04-23 05:49:27.000000000', 'message': 'Remove db layer hard-code permission checks for quota_class_get_all_by_name

This patches remove the hard-code permission checks for db call
quota_class_get_all_by_name.

For v2 api, there already have same hard-code permission checks in REST API
layer, so it is back-compatible.

For v2.1 api, for distinguish show and update permission, this patch adds
new rule for show method.

Partially implements bp nova-api-policy-final-part

UpgradeImpact: Due to the db layer permission checks deleted. There need

commit_message:
Remove db layer hard-code permission checks for quota_class_get_all_by_name

This patch removes the hard-code permission checks for db call
quota_class_get_all_by_name.

For v2 api, there already have same hard-code permission checks in REST API
layer, so it is back-compatible.

For v2.1 api, to distinguish show and update permission, this patch adds
new rule for show method.

Partially implements bp nova-api-policy-final-part

SecurityImpact
UpgradeImpact: Due to the db layer permission checks deleted, they need
default policy rule instead of that. In this patch,
"os_compute_api:os-quota-class-sets:show" was updated with a default
rule. Admin will be notfied to update their policy configure file to keep
the behavior as before.

Change-Id: I02da6cc8c766e5f43689449ef63121122f537b5b

commit_message:
Make serial console configurable

Add serial_console section to nova.conf template.
The section attributes are enabled, base_url, port_range and
proxyclient_address.

Depends-On: I9c4061ea196a511f7fb306f3130db75f4ba52ff1
Closes_Bug: 1470025

Change-Id: I5336a9bc83669e7200afe68702031f2a13d1a2e0

commit_message:
Remove tox and requirements hacking

We were hacking the Routes package problem due to changes to the global
requirements. Now with the following change merged, we don't have this
problem (https://review.openstack.org/#/c/201133/).

Change-Id: Ie7cbfc3846cca1660398bae44c8778e6b3b1bcd3

commit_message:
Simplify parameters for rpc_backend

It is not needed anymore to specify the whole python namespace
for the backends, and in Liberty this option is completely removed
(see https://review.openstack.org/189201).

This patch keeps backwards compatibility with the previous default
parameters.

Change-Id: I5c84def51bcda593c89c3897c52fb4e8e663e121

commit_message:
Return 404 for images in pending_delete status

Currently, glance image-delete and nova image-delete api returns a
403 for images with pending_delete status.

This patch would fix the behavior to return 404 for any image with
the 'deleted' flag set to True.

This only applies to the v1 APIs since the v2 APIs already use the
same flag.

DocImpact
APIImpact
Change-Id: I5e434bb3edd766f330951b72bdd4f0f8fc807edb
Closes-Bug: #1446326

commit_message:
puppetfile: Bump puppetlabs-inifile module to 1.4.x

Puppetlabs just released the 1.4.0 version of inifile module,
this version include the fix (MODULES-1599: Match only on space
and tab whitespace after k/v separator).

This patch is related to https://review.openstack.org/#/c/195003/

Change-Id: I9fcd5823b70dacbe1e41737f05d52a175481d57d

commit_message:
gate-nova-python34 sometimes test failed on test_save_updates_numa_topology

gate-nova-python34 test failed on test_save_updates_numa_topology in
following jenkins build log.
http://logs.openstack.org/19/201019/1/check/gate-nova-python34/1e74b65/console.html

The difference of expected value and actual value two are
nova_object.changes in cells object. They have same element with
different order. This is because of the order of _changed_fields
was not always same. Therefore the two value's order will be different.

Use mock object to patch InstanceNUMATopology object's _to_json function.

Change-Id: Idad2d06ea2d42b123d7460cb78b0954f23c18563
Closes-Bug: 1473949

commit_message:
Add tool to build a doc latex pdf

The sphinx latex generation generates invalid latex that won't compile
when you try to use it.[1][2] This commit adds a helper script to generate
the sphinx latex and then modify it so it'll work. It depends on
ImageMagick convert and sed being available to work.

[1] https://github.com/sphinx-doc/sphinx/issues/1907
[2] https://github.com/sphinx-doc/sphinx/issues/1959

Change-Id: Id289c10907aaddae2483f18b39063852ec699d66

commit_message:
Update pylint pin to 1.4.4

Neutron uses pylint as part of a voting pep8 job. A pylint
dependency (logilab-common 1.0) released which broke pylint.
The pylint team then released 1.4.4 to fix that.

Change-Id: Ibad8cd2911efbe075ea2629c543f6ce1f216c938

commit_message:
Revert "Implement compare-and-swap for instance update"

This reverts commit 5b4083f8cbbcca18ea5896f06b371e29b244d0e2

There are gate failures spiking with InstanceUpdateConflict
since this merged, the exception isn't being handled like
how UnexpectedTaskStateError would be handled, so we need
to think about this some more before landing it.

Change-Id: I1d2868eac456052a9ce05a7b8c838eff817d89a4
Closes-Bug: #1474550

commit_message:
Add basic external test plugin support to tempest

This commit starts the basic framework for using external plugins in
tempest. It adds a new singleton class to load the plugins once from
stevedore and also provides an interface for different steps in the
tempest execution to use plugins as well as in-tree code.

As part of this an ABC abstract class is created to simplify the
plugin side creation. Eventually the expectation is that this
abstract class will live in tempest-lib. But, for right now while
this feature is still experimental and under development this will
likely change frequently so it'll live in tempest for the time being.

Partially Implements bp external-plugin-interface

Change-Id: I8ebabdb4ce9f4d3b3aca375158835f907d5ca315

commit_message:
Executor docstring & attribute tweaks

Adjust some docstrings to better align with the class
they are attached to. Also changes some docstrings for
the pooled executor (as it is an abstraction on-top of
async executors, and is not tied to threads anymore) and
correctly denote this on its attributes that others can
and are overriding. 

Change-Id: I2eaaeed3aa0ae64eb5c82843381b7518ac508ac1

commit_message:
Add usage documentation for oslo_service.service module

This change adds description of various ways of launching a service
and provides information on supported signals.

Description of launcher classes is moved from oslo_service.service.py
to usage.rst

Change-Id: I7b6a5337de4c25ad16bd33be48daa8ef8bf3b6f5

commit_message:
Add include on ::mysql::server

Mysql server is referenced however not included in this file which
causes problems if you have not already included it.

Change-Id: I833c357cb536b5e1f423dceb89d61530b32a4ee6
Closes-Bug: #1472837

commit_message:
Remove duplicated setting of IMAGE_URLS from README.md

The default setting of IMAGE_URLS is given in stackrc, while 
tools/xen/README.md will still suggest user to set it in localrc with 
a duplicated value(i.e. http://download.cirros-cloud.net/0.3.4/cirros
-0.3.4-x86_64-uec.tar.gz) and thus causes a conflict of image upload.

Closes-Bug: #1473432

Change-Id: I910e5daa192b4186f93a58790f761ee0f3808cbb

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-03-05 19:45:25.000000000', 'message': "Add FETCHING notification state (not persisted)

When arguments are being fetched it is useful to
notify others that this is about to happen and then
pass those arguments to listeners of RUNNING/REVERTING
so that they can do things with those arguments (if
they so desire).

This adds a new state notification before RUNNING/REVERTING
that allows users to become aware that arguments are being
retrieved (which depending on the backend and overall
flow complexity may take a while).

New notification keys 'task_arguments' and 'retry_arguments'
are emitted in the RUNNING/REVERTING states that now include
the arguments that will be executed/reverted with (for the
task/retry that is being notified about).

Change-Id: I67303219e7fed472d0cf327efc893c42ff49907f

Change-Id: I67303219e7fed472d0cf327efc893c42ff49907f
"}]
commit_message:
Add FETCHING notification state (not persisted)

When arguments are being fetched it is useful to
notify others that this is about to happen and then
pass those arguments to listeners of RUNNING/REVERTING
so that they can do things with those arguments (if
they so desire).

This adds a new state notification before RUNNING/REVERTING
that allows users to become aware that arguments are being
retrieved (which depending on the backend and overall
flow complexity may take a while).

New notification keys 'task_arguments' and 'retry_arguments'
are emitted in the RUNNING/REVERTING states that now include
the arguments that will be executed/reverted with (for the
task/retry that is being notified about).

Change-Id: I67303219e7fed472d0cf327efc893c42ff49907f

commit_message:
Declare the CONF variable

In the several places the CONF variable is used from the murano.config.
This patch declares the local CONF variable and uses the oslo_config library.

Change-Id: I1f9a42f7f2cf7fef2cf0d63b185428dfddd9e78e

Fix add default images to IMAGE_URLS

When IMAGE_URLS is set in localrc default images should still be
added to IMAGE_URLS.

commit_message:
Remove ngimages index.html domain header

Per Lin's comment on https://review.openstack.org/#/c/200324/

Removing the domain header. Current images page doesn't include
page header block, so removing that block entirely.

Change-Id: I2d854f4918dfeac72432719910e5d06a20f5d96b
Partially-Implements: blueprint angularize-images-table

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-07-14 18:53:38.000000000', 'message': 'make test_save_updates_numa_topology stable accross python versions

test_save_updates_numa_topology has a rather complex nova object to
represent numa. This includes items which are sets, but must be
converted to lists for json. This is not a stable output operation
across all space and time. The mock comparitor was failing here some
times because of it.

Instead, we can manually inspect the parameter in question with our
json comparitor to ensure that it is correct.

Change-Id: Ibfa441356d10417e2b1e092826562ad03d8cfd02

times because of it.

Instead, we can manually inspect the parameter in question with our

commit_message:
make test_save_updates_numa_topology stable across python versions

test_save_updates_numa_topology has a rather complex nova object to
represent numa. This includes items which are sets, but must be
converted to lists for json. This is not a stable output operation
across all space and time. The mock comparator was failing here some
times because of it.

Instead, we can manually inspect the parameter in question with our
json comparator to ensure that it is correct.

Closes-Bug: #1473949

Change-Id: Ibfa441356d10417e2b1e092826562ad03d8cfd02

commit_message:
Mask passwords in debug log on user password operations

When a user is created, they change their password, or admin
changes their password and debug logging is enabled, the value of
the user's password was logged. The value should be masked.

Change-Id: I07b7441378fb630f01204d6b656b218f6b94dd5a
Closes-Bug: #1465922
(cherry picked from commit fbdb100e656b19958589fa659bf9d95303e76ab8)

commit_message:
Place an accurate lower bound on pbr

Without this version, markers will fail to install in a growing number
of projects.

Change global-requirements to prevent
pip -r requirements.txt; pip install .
failing with an already installed and too old for setup_requires pbr.

Change update.py to signal to setuptools the minimum version required,
giving clearer error messages in the case of downgrades during
devstack.

Change-Id: I074274b470a7a4f2c95211677b135038ab2c942c

commit_message:
Stop adding extra newline after unparseable lines.

I have a project that includes a requirement line this:

    -e git://git.openstack.org/openstack/neutron.git#egg=neutron

Every time update.py runs against the file, it adds an extra newline
after this.  For example, if I run update.py a few times, I'll have a
few new lines in the file.  This patch prevents the extra newlines
from getting added.

Change-Id: I92d02a45c437025b16df067d7b58a3727d42c0e0
Signed-off-by: Russell Bryant <rbryant@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Bump oslotest to 1.6.1 for functional tests

There's a new functional test base class for oslotest that groks
clouds.yaml files from devstack. It would be great to be able to
depend on it broadly.

Depends-On: Ibd2d473fce878424e8a6d1c76e81088e575e619b
Change-Id: I5a0d822b9b5294f41b0f668f0a7f07334d9f88e6

commit_message:
Bump 1.9.0 to oslo.utils

The fileutils is graduated in the oslo.utils library for the 1.8.0 version.
And The missed write_to_tempfile function was added in the 1.9.0 version.

Implements: blueprint graduate-fileutils

Depends-On: I661dd222da6386a7dbcf854958a63e59b13e9ba4 (oslo.utils)
Change-Id: I51ba9076e1fbc16145ee2311f47b7768c16dcb20

commit_message:
patch open in a context manager instead of decorator

Because of the test inheritance test_keypair_import is getting called
3 times. It appears that the mock for open builtins is getting torn
down after it's first use, and not correctly built again on subsequent calls.

In the gate, this is a race, because we have 3 tests and 8 workers,
and this will only fail if 2 or more of the tests happen to be
allocated to the same worker. This can be reproduced locally with:

  tox -e py27 -- --concurrency=1

Converting this to the context manager usage of mock appears to
resolve the issue.

Change-Id: I46b50df69ce0c353d2dc221ad0e6484957561bf9

commit_message:
Retain atom 'revert' result (or failure)

When a atom is reverted it can be useful to retain the
result of that 'revert' method being called, so that it
can be later analyzed (or used for various purposes) so
adjust the storage, and actions to enable it to be stored.

Change-Id: I38a9a5f3bf7550e924468bb4a86652cb8beb306c

commit_message:
Modified testscenario for micro version 2.4

Microversion 2.4 adds 'reserved' status in os-fixed-ips.
Currently it's functional tests runs against both v2 (which are skipped)
and v2.1(with version 2.4).

Microversion tests do not need to run  against v2. It should only run for 2.4

This commit fix that by defining testscenario for 2.4 microversion.
Which will make 2.4 microversion tests to run only for 2.4 and by
appending "(2_4)" string in 2.4 tests ids to have clear and readable tests
names for microversion 2.4.

Change-Id: I3638013133f9eddd0c8a53ba63f340861ff9caa1

commit_message:
Revert "Use ubuntu-trusty for multi-node tests"

This reverts commit 2b5b800d4fc48724da66e72e03812222125d3667. These new
images cannot be reliably uploaded to rackspace which makes iterating on
image updates/fixes very difficult. Switch back to the old image (using
new shorter hostnames) to get multinode working again. We can switch
back when we have uploads sorted out.

Change-Id: I46e051a4a566ae400c2fc153ad72596c853af32c

Hey everyone,

You should all be aware of this "bug". https://bugs.launchpad.net/keystone/+bug/1470635

The summary is endpoints created with v3 are not visible to v2.0 clients. v3 is backwards compatible, not forward compatible.

Looking through the playbooks it appears you create the initial endpoint with the service_token with the v3 endpoint. Unless I am missing something in a previous task, this may prevent you from viewing endpoints with the v2.0 clients.

'}, {'created': '2015-06-30 23:41:46.000000000', 'message': "Upgrade the Keystone library to use v3

In order to enable and deploy federated Keystone, we need to use version
3 of the Keystone API and the v3 Keystone Client. This work begins that
transition by having a set of backwards compatible library commands.

Specifically, this commit updates the keystone library to use v3
Keystone Client and the usage of ensure_tenant in the os_keystone tasks
to use the v3 admin url.

In version 3 of Keystone's Endpoints (Catalog) API each endpoint only
has one URL and has separate interface types (public, internal, admin).
This change updates all uses of ensure_endpoint to structure the
endpoint data in a better way for the ensure_endpoint command in the
keystone module. As a result, some incidents where internalurl and
adminurl were swapped have been fixed.

Partially-implements: blueprint keystone-federation
Change-Id: I2cd4f505e850b4b113452abc25ee00d486b1637d

3 of the Keystone API and the v3 Keystone Client. This work begins that
transition by having a set of backwards compatible library commands.

Specifically, this commit updates the keystone library to use v3
Keystone Client and the usage of ensure_tenant in the os_keystone tasks
to use the v3 admin url.

In version 3 of Keystone's Endpoints (Catalog) API each endpoint only
has one URL and has separate interface types (public, internal, admin).
This change updates all uses of ensure_endpoint to structure the
endpoint data in a better way for the ensure_endpoint command in the
keystone module. As a result, some incidents where internalurl and
adminurl were swapped have been fixed.

Partially-implements: blueprint keystone-federation
Change-Id: I2cd4f505e850b4b113452abc25ee00d486b1637d

commit_message:
Upgrade the Keystone library to use v3

In order to enable and deploy federated Keystone, we need to use version
3 of the Keystone API and the v3 Keystone Client. This work begins that
transition by having a set of backwards compatible library commands.

Specifically, this commit updates the keystone library to use v3
Keystone Client and the usage of ensure_tenant in the os_keystone tasks
to use the v3 admin url.

In version 3 of Keystone's Endpoints (Catalog) API each endpoint only
has one URL and has separate interface types (public, internal, admin).
This change updates all uses of ensure_endpoint to structure the
endpoint data in a better way for the ensure_endpoint command in the
keystone module. As a result, some incidents where internalurl and
adminurl were swapped have been fixed.

Note:
In new deployments the endpoints will be created using the v3 API and
will therefore not be available via the v2 API. This will be a breaking
change to legacy CLI clients. The openstack CLI should be used instead.

DocImpact
Related-Bug: #1470635
Partially-implements: blueprint keystone-federation
Change-Id: I2cd4f505e850b4b113452abc25ee00d486b1637d

commit_message:
Make sure configure-vm mac doesn't start negative

The original version of this code allowed for the possibility of
generating macs with negative numbers (consider generating 100 macs,
with a random start value of 0xaa).

While this is unlikely to be a problem in real-world uses of this
code, it's still a potential bug if someone starts to push on the
limits of what is supported.

Change-Id: Ia42da0ece5ab3fbeccd6b4d8a4125c1bf5a658d0

commit_message:
Fix problem with using volumes for HDFS data in vanilla plugin

Using 'dfs.namenode.data.dir' param wrong. Should use
'dfs'datanode.data.dir' for storing datanode data

commit_message:
ml2: l3 plugin doesn't always has dvr_deletens_if_no_port method

Since dvr_deletens_if_no_port isn't part of l3 interface,
ml2 plugin shouldn't assume that l3 plugin has dvr_deletens_if_no_port
method.
Otherwise it results in attribute error in delete_port method.

Change-Id: I9fd47642409d71082ba39b7f67595f691945bcec
Closes-Bug: #1474265

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-07-14 14:51:15.000000000', 'message': "Use an Anchor when service is managed

Today, Keystone resources (domains, tenants, etc) are created only if
'keystone' service is started.
When running Keystone in WSGI, the autorequire is broken for those
resources.
Adding 'httpd' in autorequire is not enough because it could fail to
orchestration issues if running another httpd resource (Horizon) that
depends on having Keystone started.

This patch is about to create an Anchor (keystone_started) in
keystone::service that require Service['keystone'] resource to be
created.
In resource types, change the autorequire to depend on the new Anchor.

With that patch, we are sure Keystone resources won't be created before
service is actually managed (running or stopped) and other resources
(Horizon, using httpd server) can also depend on this Anchor if needed.

Change-Id: Ie72b65b6be224cadc8730e050bec38d2face5dfd
Closes-bug: #1474059
(cherry picked from commit c11b0408ef0f2d98749106cabc47c7d0b9268b4c)
"}]
commit_message:
Use an Anchor when service is managed

Today, Keystone resources (domains, tenants, etc) are created only if
'keystone' service is started.
When running Keystone in WSGI, the autorequire is broken for those
resources.
Adding 'httpd' in autorequire is not enough because it could fail to
orchestration issues if running another httpd resource (Horizon) that
depends on having Keystone started.

This patch is about to create an Anchor (keystone_started) in
keystone::service that require Service['keystone'] resource to be
created.
In resource types, change the autorequire to depend on the new Anchor.

With that patch, we are sure Keystone resources won't be created before
service is actually managed (running or stopped) and other resources
(Horizon, using httpd server) can also depend on this Anchor if needed.

Change-Id: Ie72b65b6be224cadc8730e050bec38d2face5dfd
Closes-bug: #1474059
(cherry picked from commit c11b0408ef0f2d98749106cabc47c7d0b9268b4c)

This patch adds environment marker to the Routes package which has
caused some problems in Nova. Previous version constraints excluded
version 2.1, which effectively forces all projects to use version 1.13
of Routes. However, version 1.13 cannot pass py34 gate. By adding this

Change-Id: I88e78d396af15811a6ed579152955f63ad73691a
'}]
commit_message:
Fix Routes version problem for py3

This patch adds environment marker to the Routes package which has
caused some problems in Nova. Previous version constraints excluded
version 2.1, which effectively forces all projects to use version 1.13
of Routes. However, version 1.13 cannot pass py34 gate. By adding this
marker, we make both py27 and py34 happy while waiting for the next
release from Routes.

Change-Id: I88e78d396af15811a6ed579152955f63ad73691a

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-07-09 16:10:17.000000000', 'message': "[HDP] Nameservice awareness for NNHA case

With the addition of NNHA in Kilo, Oozie continued to be pointed at only
one namenode's IP. This change directs EDP jobs to the nameservice,
which defaults to the cluster's name as sent to HDP.

As it is intended primarily for backport, to allow Sahara's EDP to
function in the NNHA case, this change takes a minimal-path approach to
resolving this issue, which can be supplemented or replaced by a more
robust solution for nameservice configuration and load balancing for all
components as time permits.

Closes-bug: 1470841
(cherry picked from commit aced37e13f1357a44b7d6f8367a4f49f559ad6c7)

Change-Id: I14ccd5b32c68d0f989b12c4485598094e8841474
"}]
commit_message:
[HDP] Nameservice awareness for NNHA case

With the addition of NNHA in Kilo, Oozie continued to be pointed at only
one namenode's IP. This change directs EDP jobs to the nameservice,
which defaults to the cluster's name as sent to HDP.

As it is intended primarily for backport, to allow Sahara's EDP to
function in the NNHA case, this change takes a minimal-path approach to
resolving this issue, which can be supplemented or replaced by a more
robust solution for nameservice configuration and load balancing for all
components as time permits.

Closes-bug: 1470841
(cherry picked from commit aced37e13f1357a44b7d6f8367a4f49f559ad6c7)

Change-Id: I14ccd5b32c68d0f989b12c4485598094e8841474

commit_message:
Fix retrieve_auth_url in case Keystone URL does not contain port.

Sahara calls retrieve_auth_url() to retrieve auth_url from input
uri. However, this function does not work correctly if input uri
does not contain port.

Change-Id: Ic7a65cd36a237d68151936404567c3bd7d068117
Closes-Bug: #1473434

commit_message:
Resolve 500 error during simultaneously deletion

We need to render not found in case if some resource was deleted
to prevent to_wrapped_dict() execution. This patch do that job.

Change-Id: Ie179869bbf15965263cff62bb35740d825b6cabf
Closes-bug: 1463068
(cherry picked from commit 3bfd3ea643502c3cab2c29b2d7ed6ea5e126b4c0)

[{'created': '2015-06-26 18:46:21.000000000', 'message': 'Use stevedore for loading monitor extensions

The compute monitor plugins were being loaded using the nova.loadables
module. This patch uses the stevedore library to load monitor
extensions. We keep the same semantics as the previous loading
mechanism: we use the CONF.compute_monitors configuration option to
winnow the set of all monitor plugins, and we ensure that no two
monitors that return the same set of metrics will be loaded.

However, this patch deprecates the CONF.compute_available_monitors
configuration option, since stevedore and setuptools entry points now
allow a set of plugins to be specified without any further configuration
options.

Change-Id: I97bf8bcd43faf9f3fe40983497c2360233d5f599
Fixes-bug: 1468012
DocImpact: deprecates the CONF.compute_available_monitors option.

commit_message:
Use stevedore for loading monitor extensions

The compute monitor plugins were being loaded using the nova.loadables
module. This patch uses the stevedore library to load monitor
extensions. We keep the same semantics as the previous loading
mechanism: we use the CONF.compute_monitors configuration option to
winnow the set of all monitor plugins, and we ensure that no two
monitors that return the same set of metrics will be loaded.

However, this patch deprecates the CONF.compute_available_monitors
configuration option, since stevedore and setuptools entry points now
allow a set of plugins to be specified without any further configuration
options.

Change-Id: I97bf8bcd43faf9f3fe40983497c2360233d5f599
Fixes-bug: 1468012
DocImpact: deprecates the CONF.compute_available_monitors option.

For projects such as Manuals and Horizon, the source directory in
zanata.xml is set to '.', which may have the unintended side-effect

commit_message:
Add excludes support for create-zanata-xml

For projects such as Manuals and Horizon, the source directory in
zanata.xml is set to '.', which may have the unintended side-effect
of the Zanata client finding .po or .pot files under dot directories.
Add a new option to create-zanata-xml, and use it for those two
projects.

Change-Id: I5fc26069c288eca130a45c6e9c5e3dd00ad2c784

commit_message:
Add OVS QoS extension agent driver

This is a prototype for the OVS agent driver for QoS
extension.
Should be adjusted to final API's once they are added

blueprint ml2-ovs-qos-with-bwlimiting

Depends-On: I9e388173dfe0eb43c961018bd687bc86f34c7a6a
Change-Id: Ie952b63e3760d1924a34676e97319ec4301effca

setting fields ordering, need to rearrange fields there by recreating
underlying OrderedDict.

Change-Id: If0f4c7014a7a68f2ff0d0f2cb06f7b1c2e28436b
Closes-Bug: #1465221

commit_message:
Fix Create User form's fields sorting for Django 1.7

Starting from Django 1.7 self.fields.keyOrder no longer works for
setting fields ordering, need to rearrange fields there by recreating
underlying OrderedDict.

Change-Id: If0f4c7014a7a68f2ff0d0f2cb06f7b1c2e28436b
Closes-Bug: #1465221
(cherry picked from commit d2f9b6604cbfbf3dc5c0328e783e27b3ef1a4e37)

[{'created': '2015-07-10 11:46:41.000000000', 'message': "Fix TemplateSyntaxError at hypervisors view

If somehow nova API service-list isn't available, listing
hypervisors at /admin/hypervisors/ ends with TemplateSyntaxError.

Expected result is that the page should load but user will
see empty list and error message.

This fix is based on idea found in other views:

openstack_dashboard/dashboards/admin/...
images/views.py
aggregate/views.py
falvors/views.pu

that on any exception while getting data (get_data), we just
return empty list and handle exception to display error message.

Closes-Bug: #1392316

Change-Id: Ia665111185abecab6a96e6c72a6088cf2fa2e02b
(cherry picked from commit 5c4e827568be429ac5227a950c9f24c578ca8fd8)
"}]
commit_message:
Fix TemplateSyntaxError at hypervisors view

If somehow nova API service-list isn't available, listing
hypervisors at /admin/hypervisors/ ends with TemplateSyntaxError.

Expected result is that the page should load but user will
see empty list and error message.

This fix is based on idea found in other views:

openstack_dashboard/dashboards/admin/...
images/views.py
aggregate/views.py
falvors/views.pu

that on any exception while getting data (get_data), we just
return empty list and handle exception to display error message.

Closes-Bug: #1392316

Change-Id: Ia665111185abecab6a96e6c72a6088cf2fa2e02b
(cherry picked from commit 5c4e827568be429ac5227a950c9f24c578ca8fd8)

(1 comment)

I considered security:managed but it seemed like it had wider-reaching implications. I want something that indicates vulnerability reporting and announcements are managed directly by the VMT, while not implying anything beyond that.

commit_message:
Add and apply vulnerability:managed tag

The VMT is building out automation and reporting for vulnerability
management processes in order to better accomodate the rapid growth
of the OpenStack ecosystem. In an order to scale consumability of
its processes beyond its current charter and capacity, a formal
acknowledgement of the list of source code repositories directly
handled by the VMT (rather than managed independently by individual
project teams) is best maintained through application of a
governance-related tag.

Change-Id: I1260839b50b6a5ff57a6649e419094f2d4f7f877

commit_message:
Revert "Change misleading TRACE to ERROR"

This reverts commit 27f7fe52fefcb81c5fe01736841d7a20149caf02

Logstash can't distinguish traces from errors now so we have
no way to do multi-line queries, which is bad.

Change-Id: I39885c6215f0c78cceb330651783f5fe1c3d307a
Closes-Bug: #1474545

commit_message:
Updated from global requirements

Issue found with mock 1.1.3:

Because of the test inheritance test_keypair_import is getting called
3 times. It appears that the mock for open builtins is getting torn
down after it's first use, and not correctly built again on subsequent calls.

In the gate, this is a race, because we have 3 tests and 8 workers,
and this will only fail if 2 or more of the tests happen to be
allocated to the same worker. This can be reproduced locally with:

  tox -e py27 -- --concurrency=1

Converting this to the context manager usage of mock appears to
resolve the issue.

Co-Authored-By: Sean Dague <sean@dague.net>

Related-Bug: https://github.com/testing-cabal/mock/issues/280

Change-Id: I9a87375d2eb6c7cf7b9124b2095a5a4bcc8e7bf3

Mike, responding to your comments on https://review.openstack.org/#/c/109837/:

I deliberately left out the backoff mechanism because I wasn't sure we'd need it in practise. However, I could be convinced to put it in.

As for the generic 'update a row with compare and swap', that's what I originally wanted to write. However, check out the weirdness with _validate_unique_server_name_query()*. The _with_expected() function is as generic as I could make it, and still allow for additional custom validation. I'll take advice on this, though.

(*) This is a unique constraint enforced in python :/ My first thought was to fix this, but I noticed that the scope of the uniqueness is configurable by the user. I decided to leave it alone."}, {'account_id': 9555, 'date': '2015-01-09 13:16:10.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7:

Sorry, rethinking the backoff: I don't think it's required. The reason is that the intended behaviour is to fail immediately. This makes sense, because we're not going to update unless our expected values haven't changed. If they did, retrying isn't likely to put them back again. The loop here is only to head off an extremely unlikely livelock situation. Exponential backoff would suggest that we're trying to break a cluster of simultaneous updates which all modify our expected values, then put them back to exactly what they were before we can do error checking, and do this repeatedly. I'd rather keep it simple until this starts showing up in logs regularly :)"}, {'account_id': 100, 'date': '2015-01-09 16:32:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

I wouldn't -1 exponential backoff (since it won't hurt), but it doesn't seem necessary either.

In our case, one thread will "win" if there is contention. As a result, it's much less likely to lose on retry since there is less contention.

This isn't like Ethernet where everyone loses and random backoff is required.

So keeping it simple seems like a win to me.'}, {'account_id': 11816, 'date': '2015-01-09 16:46:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

matt -

I have a notion for how the generic part of "compare and swap" would look and I can definitely work out the "additional select" problem at the end.  there are several ways to update an object with state that isn't to be flushed, it's just the kind of thing that is better off in a dedicated, generic function so that it can be tested in isolation and re-used.     my notion here is that the calling code would either load, or manually construct, the object that is to be the "specimen" - the row that we want to UPDATE.  those fields which are present (or optionally an explicit list of field names) would go into formulating the UPDATE using more or less your _with_expected scheme.   it will do the UPDATE and the iteration, we can have the "backoff timer" be an optional behavior within that so problem solved there, and things like the "hostname query" can be just passed along into the generic function as additional "validations" to occur within the scope of each attempt.   the routine will then return the object with the new fields and its state set up such that its the same as if it were loaded from a SELECT (that is, we know the instance already so we can re-implement a shorthand form of "synchronize_session").'}, {'account_id': 9555, 'date': '2015-01-09 17:01:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

Michael, would you do this in oslo.db, or SQLA?'}, {'account_id': 11816, 'date': '2015-01-09 17:06:00.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7:

it would be in oslo.db.  it's a use case.  if it's really amazing, maybe it could be in a SQLA FAQ entry or example at some point but typically, adding things to SQLAlchemy makes people think they need it without any clue what it's for, so I'm not too quick to add very specific things like this."}, {'account_id': 11816, 'date': '2015-01-09 17:07:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

on reason this is tough to really generalize as a SQLA feature is building out that query based on attributes can run into the weeds really w'}, {'account_id': 11816, 'date': '2015-01-09 17:09:21.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7:

trying that again:

on reason this is tough to really generalize as a SQLA feature is building out that query based on attributes can run into the weeds really quick for odder use cases, mappings against multiple tables, probably other things.  once its in SQLA, it has to work in every case ever, and if any cases don't work, even if i document those caveats in huge blinky lights people still report them as bugs.   so, likely not worth it up front."}, {'account_id': 11816, 'date': '2015-01-09 20:58:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

where's the rationale for supporting the use case that the "values" we test for in _with_expected() must be one of a series of values, and even a series of values where one of those values may be NULL?  The use that I see in _instance_update(), in both this and jay's patch, appears to be sending only a dictionary with two or three single scalar values.

the scheme I have in mind can do something (a little less nice looking) to make this possible but it doesn't look necessary as of yet.'}, {'account_id': 9555, 'date': '2015-01-10 23:56:49.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7:

Incidentally, I looked at the neutron review you linked, and I agree that compare and swap isn't the right tool to use there. I left a review. It's certainly not the only tool in the box. I think it's appropriate here, though.

'}, {'created': '2014-12-12 14:10:15.000000000', 'message': "Implement compare_and_swap for instance update

This patch reworks nova.db.sqlalchemy.api._instance_update to remove a
race condition that exists in a critical section of code that
retrieves the instance record from the database, does some checks of
both the new values and existing values of instance fields, and then
tries to update the database with the new values.

Instead of using a SELECT FOR UPDATE, which uses a write-intent lock
on the records that the SELECT statement produces, we instead use an
optimistic compare-and-swap strategy that takes no locks and attempts
to update the instance record while verifying that the record being
updated contains expected values for a set of fields. The algorithm is
lock and obstruction-free, meaning that it allows other threads to
make progress, even other threads that are updating the same instance
record in the database.

To implement the lock-free compare-and-swap algorithm, we construct an
SQLAlchemy ORM query which touches only the expected row, then
add WHERE conditions for the expected 'compare' values. We also add a
NOT EXISTS clause to ensure uniqueness of any updated hostname.

We call update on this filtered query with the 'swap' values, and
check how many rows were updated. This statement will only update the
row if all the expected 'compare' values matched.

If the update didn't return any rows we do some additional checks to
determine the specific error, which maintains the previous behaviour.
There's a small chance of a race when checking for an error if the
expected update conditions were not met when we tried the UPDATE, but
were met when we fetch the instance for error checking. We handle this
by trying again if we don't find an error. We introduce a new error,
InstanceUpdateFailed, for the exceptionally unlikely event this happens
3 times in a row.

_instance_update() is simplified by having it return only the updated
instance_ref. instance_update_and_get_original() is updated to fetch
the old value itself before calling _instance_update().

_validate_unique_server_name() is refactored to return a query rather
than a success value, which allows us to use it as a NOT EXISTS
subquery.

Change-Id: I9cd0f4b620e639b238555983bf6d58deafbaefeb

commit_message:
Implement compare-and-swap for instance update

This patch reworks nova.db.sqlalchemy.api._instance_update to remove a
race condition that exists in a critical section of code that
retrieves the instance record from the database, does some checks of
both the new values and existing values of instance fields, and then
tries to update the database with the new values.

We update the value using update_on_match, which does an optimistic,
atomic, lock-free, compare-and-swap on the object. If the update
fails, we do some additional checks to determine the specific error,
which maintains the previous behaviour. There's an exceptionally
small chance of a race when checking for an error if the expected
update conditions were not met when we tried the UPDATE, but were met
when we fetch the instance for error checking. We handle this by
raising a new error, InstanceUpdateConflict.

_instance_update() is simplified by having it return only the updated
instance_ref. instance_update_and_get_original() is updated to fetch
the old value itself before calling _instance_update().

Closes-bug: #1297375
Change-Id: I9cd0f4b620e639b238555983bf6d58deafbaefeb

commit_message:
Remove the --dhcp option to network list

The --dhcp option lists agents, not networks.  This does not make
a lot of sense.  Another command should be created to list agents.

BackwardsIncompatibleImpact
Closes-Bug: #1472613

Change-Id: I5ecfe3fc046a07eb64a4dabd41dbd99de7c2215f

commit_message:
RPM distribution packaging of OpenStack

Host all packaging git repos for rpm based distributions in the
/openstack namespace in order to have gating and review of changes
to the packaging close to the actual OpenStack development.

Change-Id: I608651414fadc0206910d2720d8d14be51a5c8af

commit_message:
Always use gate- instead of check- (zaqar)

Change pipeline name to only use "gate", we do not need the
differentiation between check and gate anymore.
This changes the pipelines configured via the file
jenkins/jobs/zaqar.yaml

Change-Id: Iecbc555f23cf9a587148442dd9dfaa73733b6a78

commit_message:
Redefine release tags to match new models

In the Liberty cycle we support new release models, which made
the current release tags taxonomy a bit unusable.

Switch to a new model taxonomy where a repository may only have
one release model:
* release:cycle-with-milestones (think keystone or nova)
* release:cycle-with-intermediary (think swift or libraries)
* release:independent (think zuul)
* release:none (think: openstack/governance)

This will clarify which release models actually exist, and
more clearly communicate to our users (and our tooling) which
model each repository follows.

We also adapt the wording of the release:managed tag to avoid
excluding swift or Oslo libraries (which do not follow the
development milestones model) from being managed if the release
team accepts them.

Change-Id: Ie58a370f2a189a421040535b99949f3fac9eb4eb

Update scripts to  check if docker is usable for $USER

docker command execution

[{'account_id': 2, 'date': '2015-06-28 14:05:58.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-06-28 14:06:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- gate-governance-docs http://docs-draft.openstack.org/38/196438/1/check/gate-governance-docs/78eea7c//doc/build/html/ : SUCCESS in 45s'}, {'account_id': 2592, 'date': '2015-06-28 21:51:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Rollcall-Vote+1 Code-Review+1

Glad this was submitted.  Neutron with provider networks is really simple and last week at the Neutron mid-cycle sat down with a few contribs to talk about how to make the docs better around getting started in this manner.'}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2015-06-29 12:09:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Functional splits that are not completed yet, like this one, is where "minimal" and "future-proof" conflict.

The question we are really asking here is: will nova-network be there forever and therefore makes a compelling starting point ? Or is it still around to cover legacy clouds but is still expected to go away at some point, and therefore a wrong starting point (especially considering the lack of a trivial migration path) ?

I'd like to hear the Nova and the Neutron side of the story before deciding on this one.'}, {'account_id': 1561, 'date': '2015-06-30 13:51:57.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1 Rollcall-Vote+1

Neutron is *VERY* close to covering everything we can think of that nova-network provides.  I still think it's the right path to keep charging down toward eventually removing nova-network.

Given that plan, I think it's the right think to do to define Neutron as the starting point.  Falling back to nova-network is one of the many things you can do once you start moving from the starting point if you find an important reason to."}, {'account_id': 964, 'date': '2015-06-30 20:43:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Until the docs are complete and can be linked to I'll mark as "needs further work" -- docs for install and config are pretty clear in the set of current projects with the tag.'}, {'account_id': 1561, 'date': '2015-06-30 20:55:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Anne, which docs are you referring to exactly?'}, {'account_id': 1561, 'date': '2015-06-30 21:02:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

For anyone that hasn't seen it, I would encourage you to check out the networking guide here:  http://docs.openstack.org/networking-guide/

If you're interested in the simpler networking use case where tenants aren't creating networks, check out scenarios 4a and 4b in the guide that discusses provider networks."}, {'account_id': 4257, 'date': '2015-06-30 22:05:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

The description of the tag says "[W]e'd like this to be a solid bit of 'seed corn' from which a larger and richer OpenStack deployment can be built out over time." I personally don't see how that vision can be fulfilled without Neutron - since there's no migration path from nova-network to Neutron, users who start without it will be stranded without a path to accessing critical networking services like LBaaS.

AIUI the tag isn't a reward for getting all of your ducks in a row (and the risk of it being treated as one was a large part of why I opposed having a tag for this at all), it's supposed to be an expression of the TC's best judgement of what beginners should deploy by default to get Nova up and running. So if the documentation is lacking - or just not organised in such a way as to offer a clear on-ramp for beginners, which seems to be more the case - then the application of the tag should be a signal that this urgently needs to be resolved to best serve users. To me it seems wrong to recommend that users default to an inflexible, soon-to-be-deprecated solution with no migration path in order to force a project to produce more/better/different documentation in order to be included - it's tantamount to holding users hostage.

If the implication of the commit message here is correct (and it was consistent with my understanding as well), the chief obstacle remaining to getting rid of nova-network is the lack of a migration path to Neutron. That may be literally the worst possible argument for recommending that new deployments start with nova-network.

BTW from a Heat perspective the need to support two different types of networking primitives is a giant pain, and the deprecation of nova-network can't come quickly enough IMHO. I imagine everyone who has to write tools to interact with multiple clouds probably feels the same.'}, {'account_id': 964, 'date': '2015-07-01 13:05:54.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I can't get to it right now, but there was a discussion in https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/liberty-neutron-gaps-concerns that made me want to point precisely to documentation that addresses one of the concerns in that etherpad.

I'll circle back to see if it has been addressed in the Networking Guide. I think a section in that guide about migration concerns would be helpful."}, {'account_id': 2750, 'date': '2015-07-06 10:11:19.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

so, here is the thing. We tried a presumptive nova-network deprecation in the past, and that went poorly. So it was undeprecated. At this point the temperature I've taken with the wide Nova team is that nova-network is probably here for the long term until there is a simple and robust enough configuration of Neutron to take over. I think a list of a lot of those things was developed at summit.

From the best that I can read the temperature of things: there is no firm plan in the Nova team at this point to deprecate nova-network again. There is a desire, but at this point the feeling is that ball is back in the Neutron camp to make a robust and simple enough model that it's not an adoption impediment to Nova. 

And only a few folks are working on that gap closing. If the TC wants to help accelerate one network stack here, the best way probably isn't this change, it's diving in and helping close those gaps and get us to a simpler place with Neutron so that we believe this is no longer a tough choice to make between nova-net and neutron, but a simple one.

Honestly, a good starting point exercise might be for all TC members to install and configure a cloud by hand using the OpenStack Install Guide, and see the experience on each side of this, and whether we feel which experience we think is best for new deployers that don't know OpenStack."}, {'account_id': 2243, 'date': '2015-07-06 13:02:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

I don't object to the wording or anything else, but IMO making Neutron a part of anything called "starter-kit" is a bit ironic (no pun intended).  Given the insights/comments from Sean I'm going ahead and voting -1.'}, {'account_id': 2, 'date': '2015-07-06 13:14:49.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Rollcall-Vote+1

I agree with Zane 100%.

Although I understand the reasonable concerns various people have about the state of various things, I think it's irresponsible for us to allow anyone to have the impression that there is a long-term vision for OpenStack with two incompatible networking APIs. Further to that, I think implying to anyone that they might want to start TODAY installing something that we know is going to go away is not doing anyone any favors.

Perhaps a TDL item from this is that we should have a version of the installation guide that focuses on the starter kit. I will go ahead and volunteer to help work on that, since otherwise it's me making suggestions for things that other people can work on.

Even before that exists, though, I think we need to add neutron to the set, because otherwise we're passively recommending new deployments of nova-network."}, {'account_id': 105, 'date': '2015-07-06 13:26:15.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

Lets add Neutron in here, FUD be damned. See Russell's comments for a crisply documented way to use Neutron in a simplistic way."}, {'account_id': 964, 'date': '2015-07-06 13:27:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

What I learned from reviewing the discussions at the Summit is that there are some steps to take to get the initial experience better for neutron:
- Use Linux Bridge instead of OVS in DevStack and in docs (the install guide is current OVS)
- The Networking guide now has this simplest scenario: http://docs.openstack.org/networking-guide/deploy_scenario4b.html and you could also take a look at that for evaluation

My vote is still -1 while I wrap my head around what works best for someone getting started.'}, {'account_id': 10980, 'date': '2015-07-06 16:08:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

I think the comments about nova-net deprecation are conflating two things.  The criteria for the network stuff in the starter tag was:
1) get a vm on the network
2) allow folks to experiment with clouds

Note that nova-net/neutron feature parity is not on that list.

nova-net and neutron both accomplish #1, but neutron has a documentation hole. neutron puts people in a better position for #2, unless we are changing our long-term guidance.

At the recent neutron mid-cycle, we sat down with the doc folks, and the "simple" neutron path with linuxbridge and provider nets will be in the default install guide for liberty, which closes the doc gap from #1.

So I might've expected this to merge in a few weeks instead of now, but I'm strongly in favor of not encouraging folks to head down a path that doesn't involving migrating from nova-net to neutron.'}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2015-07-07 08:56:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I think there are 3 options here.

1- We consider that nova-network will be there forever, and it's up to the Neutron team to build an automated migration path if they want to ever be considered as an upgrade to the starter kit. In which case we should reject that change and never include Neutron in the starter kit.

2- We consider that nova-network is a temporary necessary evil, and that Neutron is far from being in a state where we can recommend it in a "starter kit". That means we don't have a good story for the starter kit -- we can't recommend a dead end in a starter kit and push more people in it. In which case I think we should abandon the starter kit concept, at least temporarily.

3- nova-network is kept for compatibility reasons, but Neutron is close enough to a state that we can recommend it in a "starter kit". In which case we should accept this change.

I'm leaning towards (3) because I don't believe in the magic migration path and I still want a starter kit. So that seems the less worse solution, and I expect things to only get better over time.'}, {'account_id': 1561, 'date': '2015-07-07 12:58:16.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Yes, I'm definitely in the #3 camp.  As I mentioned in an earlier comment, Neutron has come quite a long way and is *very* close to covering all nova-network gaps.  

Further, I don't even think nova-network compatibility is all that relevant when we're talking about a starting point.  I think it's a perfectly reasonable place to start, provides a lot more interesting networking capabilities, and is certainly preferable to putting people on the path of having to deal with a migration later."}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2015-07-07 14:38:14.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Rollcall-Vote+1

If we're going to recommend a starting place for users, it shouldn't be a dead-end."}, {'account_id': 2750, 'date': '2015-07-07 15:07:51.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

so, I'd be +1 on this if we can get 4b in http://docs.openstack.org/networking-guide/deploy_scenario4b.html to be the default for the install guide - http://docs.openstack.org/kilo/install-guide/install/apt/content/section_neutron-networking.html

The current default documents we have on how to install and configure neutron are very far from that model, and produce a level of complexity that I think is beyond starter kit feasibility.

Honestly, in spending more time walking through doing local install via the install guide, I think cinder probably should be dropped from the list as well as a change. While nova doesn't provide strong guaruntees on system disks, it's probably good enough for starter kit."}, {'account_id': 2750, 'date': '2015-07-07 15:10:39.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

@zane, @monty - my concern really isn't nova-network parity of features, or even migration, it's straight simplicity of a working environment. I think the 4b scenario in the networking guide definitely gets us there, but we need that back into our normal install guide as a baseline. And then reference the networking guide for additional interesting configurations."}, {'account_id': 1561, 'date': '2015-07-07 15:19:07.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I see this change a bit differently.

If the install guide is aimed at documenting a starting point, then what we tag (with any additional criteria) should signal what we think should be documented there.  I don't think it should be the other way around.  The tag isn't a reward for getting all the docs in order, it's our signal for what we think should be considered as the starting point, and the hope is that docs, etc. would fall in line behind that.

commit_message:
Add neutron to starter-kit:compute

While nova-network is still supported because of concerns about
migration paths, neutron should be as strongly recommended for any new
deployments as is humanly possible so that we can ultimately get
ourselves out of the mess of having two network stacks.

Since starter-kit:compute is intended to help point a finger at what
people should install when trying things out, we should certainly not
imply that they install a network stack that we plan on deleting in the
future. Neutron in provider-vlan/linuxbridge mode is dead simple in not
requiring openvswitch or SDN, and still gets new users a cloud that is
upwards flexible with the future.

Change-Id: I91bce1bcc51121a8a577cff478fdc91002b689b4

It's possible it'll work (for now) with >= in nova.  It doesn't in neutron, so I imagine it's only a matter of time."}, {'account_id': 8190, 'date': '2015-07-09 20:41:33.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I think that is due to neutron having the win32 dependencies in its requirements file.  This being a nova project shouldn't have that issue unless nova puts those dependencies in.

However, there was an interesting discussion on this in openstack-infra the other day.

http://eavesdrop.openstack.org/irclogs/%23openstack-infra/%23openstack-infra.2015-07-03.log.html

Search for win32

The theory (which did hold true for neutron-powervm) was that if the other requirements were more in line, it would resolve the issue.

But if we find that to not be the case, I believe fungi was open to the idea of incrementing.

With that said, rather than deviate from the global-requirements...then I think we instead need to go work with infra to determine if a global-requirements update is needed.

This will be something we are continually re-syncing on."}, {'account_id': 14070, 'date': '2015-07-09 20:48:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Code-Review

commit_message:
Set DocumentRoot for devstack plugin

Rather than defaulting to /var/www use /var/www/logs so that we can
copy test results into there and then check os-loganalyze works

Change-Id: I7372cae8260b3454906fa9a63e10263a6265f47c

commit_message:
WIP - injectjs - a Django command to inject JS

This Djanog command automatically discovers and injects
JavaScript code to html page.

NOTE:
This work is in progress, still working on how to pass in
arguments.

It is working now with the hard coded data. To place with
it, one needs to run below commands in terminal before
starting/resatrting web server:

> source .venv/bin/activate
> ./manage.py injectjs

Change-Id: Ifd05484a860ba6977dc4e9d43df37bfbbb31a30d
Partially-Implements: blueprint auto-js-file-finding

commit_message:
Disable python3 tests failing due to Routes < 2.0

At now, global-requirements has an entry:
Routes!=2.0,!=2.1,>=1.12.3
and this leads to Routes < 2.0 which is not compatible
with Python 3. This blocks updating of global requirements [1].
To avoid the situation, this commit disables python 3 related
error due to Routes version.

Closes-Bug: #1474266
Related to blueprint neutron-python3

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/182746/

Change-Id: If5e6355505361cbefe04487b6d47ab9cc6ba861c

Serialize port binding operation with db-access semaphore

port initiated by rpc request.

I'd like to understand the workflow a bit better -- currently in most cases we expect projects not to be in governance before they show up here.  If it's an add to an existing program, governance trails project-config and Depends-On it.  If it's a new program, then it's the other way around, but still this job will emit the error until the governance change lands.  The more important thing in that case is the Depends-On.

(I could see automatic validation with this script via a zuul-cloner driven integration-test that checks out governance with the Depends-On.  If we also standardized on setting Needed-By in the reverse case, we could probably do that too.  That's extra complex.)"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-07-14 18:06:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified-1

warn on projects not in governance

Print a warning for projects not in the governance repo as a convenience
to the reviewer for patches asking for new projects to be added.

Change-Id: I620217503918a41534c7149ffcf98bdf812adce0

Keystone also handle /identity and /identity_admin

When configured to run under Apache Httpd, keystone will also
handle requests on /identity (public) and /identity_admin (admin).
