Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

    IRC: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/IRC
    Workflow: http://docs.openstack.org/infra/manual/developers.html

 /dev/sdl3 ceph journal, for /dev/sdm1

/dev/sdm :

/dev/sdn :
 /dev/sdn1 ceph data, active, cluster ceph, osd.43, journal /dev/sdl4'}, {'account_id': 15373, 'date': '2015-07-13 18:18:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Sorry, from the ceph-disk-list output I have failed to understand what could be wrong so far. The modified instructions look to work for me on your output. Could you provide more info that could help, e.g. puppet logs?'}, {'account_id': 13950, 'date': '2015-07-14 07:01:52.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

As per example we are using something like this in hiera:

ceph::profile::params::osds:
  '/dev/sdc':
    journal: '/dev/sdf'
  '/dev/sdd':
    journal: '/dev/sdf'
  '/dev/sde':

so $name and thus $title is the disk and not the partition. but the new matches only will match the partition. so no existing osd data disk is detectet and puppet fails with:


 ceph-disk prepare /dev/sdi /dev/sdl
 ceph-disk: Error: Device is mounted: /dev/sdi1"}, {'account_id': 15373, 'date': '2015-07-14 07:54:36.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Thank you for the report!

Actually I didn't like much 'ceph-disk list | grep ...' thing we have currently, but thought it could live so far without large modifications. Recently I made a pull request to modify ceph so  'ceph-disk list $data' could work and be used instead of grepping the output:

https://github.com/ceph/ceph/pull/5097

But still we have to cope with older versions. I will work on a proper fix."}, {'account_id': 15373, 'date': '2015-07-14 19:17:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

The fix is published to review:

https://review.openstack.org/201730'}]

commit_message:
osd: fix pattern when matching ${data}

It could give false positive e.g. if looking for /srv/data while
/srv/data1 already exists.

Change-Id: I42a20a9d871bc3033b42693eefca05ba73766d33

commit_message:
Add Pluggable IPAM Backend Part 1

Add methods for allocating/deallocating ips using IPAM driver.
Methods are covered by unit tests and currently used only by them.

For pluggable IPAM case ipam driver may execute calls to third-party servers.
It means we can't rely on database transaction rollback in case of failure.
So if any bulk ip allocation/deallocation fails rollback should be done
on third-party servers as well.
Any completed ip allocation should be explicitly deallocated in case of
failure, and vise versa for failure on deallocation.
Try-except block is used to do manual rollback actions.
After rollback actions are done, exception is reraised and local db
transaction rollback occurs.

Pluggable IPAM was divided into two parts to keep review size small.
Following patches are expected to use these methods for ip address
allocation.

Partially-Implements: blueprint neutron-ipam

Change-Id: I8bb836c9883e189b065698ae0a862b2d909d5cbf

commit_message:
Always use gate- instead of check- (m-s*)

Change pipeline name to only use "gate", we do not need the
differentiation between check and gate anymore.
This changes the pipelines configured via files in jenkins/jobs/[m-s]*
(excluding projects.yaml).

Change-Id: Ib75f491924d75f4892a0ff2e4871b40c6e56522b

I am not entirely convinced that ignoring exceptions is inappropriate, but if it is an issue - it is general and not especially a security concern.

At the very least, this should probably not be as serious as SEVERITY: MEDIUM.

Do you have any history of vulnerabilities found in software due to their use of ignoring exceptions?'}, {'account_id': 11716, 'date': '2015-07-08 15:18:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

I really do feel that this is a particularly bad practice in general. From the security perspective, silently ignoring errors that might otherwise show up an attacking trying to fuzz or otherwise mess about with your running service is only going to be bad. Lots of unexpected exceptions in a running service is always going to be a cause for investigation, especially if nothing has really changed.

As for precedent, no I actually cant think of a documented issue around this, its more the smoke that may indicate some other fire. I can downgrade the severity if people feel MEDIUM is too harsh.

There are perhaps some legitimate situations where it is OK silently ignore exceptions (though I struggle to think of any) in those rare cases we have "#nosec"'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-07-08 15:40:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Verified+1

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- gate-bandit-python34 http://logs.openstack.org/82/199582/4/check/gate-bandit-python34/46e25e8/ : SUCCESS in 45s
- gate-bandit-pep8 http://logs.openstack.org/82/199582/4/check/gate-bandit-pep8/f2f1d97/ : SUCCESS in 40s
- gate-bandit-python27 http://logs.openstack.org/82/199582/4/check/gate-bandit-python27/a9cb55f/ : SUCCESS in 50s'}, {'account_id': 11029, 'date': '2015-07-08 15:52:14.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

Have you run this test against any of the OpenStack projects yet?  I'd be interested to see how many cases are flagged right off the bat, and will do so myself later today if someone else doesn't get there first.."}, {'account_id': 11716, 'date': '2015-07-08 16:02:13.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

It finds some in Keystone (not the latest), that's all I have tested with so far"}, {'account_id': 979, 'date': '2015-07-08 16:06:01.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

Following Python's mantra of Easier to Ask for Forgiveness than Permission. -- http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Python_syntax_and_semantics#Exceptions

I can think of situations where Exceptions are embraced, rather than a sign of error.  A good example is:

# mkdir -p in python
def mkdir_p(path):
    try:
        os.makedirs(path)
    except OSError as exc:
        if exc.errno == errno.EEXIST and os.path.isdir(path):
            pass
        else: raise 

I am not quite sure how this example would run under this proposed test, as it is still conditional.

That said, having real data of this test against openstack/* projects would be useful. If it is a small handful, then I suppose adding #nosec is ok.... but I do feel LOW severity is more suitable.

I would hope that attempts to break/fuzz would be caught first by sheer workload, rather than depending on exceptions that are ignored."}, {'account_id': 11716, 'date': '2015-07-08 16:09:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

that code block would not trigger the test to fail, care is taken to ensure that only situations where the Except block is simply "pass" will cause an issue, I am OK with dropping this to LOW severity, and yes we should see some real data for sure.'}, {'account_id': 11716, 'date': '2015-07-08 16:13:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

in support of this test I might offer up "Errors should never pass silently" from PEP20 the Zen of Python (https://www.python.org/dev/peps/pep-0020/)'}, {'account_id': 979, 'date': '2015-07-08 16:19:45.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

Ah Touché, I can't disagree with that.

What do you think of examples such as:
https://github.com/openstack/nova/blob/2d1fbcbf63895712a27970cd0a7e1cb2f90d2a62/nova/utils.py#L534"}, {'account_id': 11716, 'date': '2015-07-08 16:31:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Yes, that does seem like a valid situation, I would suggest using "nosec" there to indicate the author has considered the situation. I agree completely that if we have a massive volume of such instances then the test may not be  appropriate. If so, then it could be tuned to trigger only when the exception type is just "Exception" perhaps. Lets see what the real data looks like.'}, {'account_id': 11861, 'date': '2015-07-08 19:16:19.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

(2 comments)

Awesome new test, I'd prefer to lower the severity to low, but I'm open to other ideas.  Please fix tab in the test files, then +2."}, {'account_id': 12000, 'date': '2015-07-09 18:21:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

(2 comments)

Just a couple nits.'}, {'account_id': 11716, 'date': '2015-07-10 09:18:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

(2 comments)

will update, thanks all'}, {'account_id': 11716, 'date': '2015-07-10 09:22:42.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-07-10 09:27:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Verified+1

- gate-bandit-python34 http://logs.openstack.org/82/199582/5/check/gate-bandit-python34/9821d10/ : SUCCESS in 37s

- gate-bandit-python27 http://logs.openstack.org/82/199582/5/check/gate-bandit-python27/9e23b79/ : SUCCESS in 52s'}, {'account_id': 979, 'date': '2015-07-10 09:29:29.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5: Code-Review+1

Great!  Are you sure Medium isn't more appropriate? (/me ducks) +1"}, {'account_id': 7063, 'date': '2015-07-10 09:44:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

I certainly agree that unqualified Try->Except->Pass blocks are bad, the grey area for me is where a specific exception type is being handled and explicitly ignored.

Looking at https://review.openstack.org/#/c/199582/5/examples/try_except_pass.py I think that the third example is probably OK. 

My suggestion:
Base behavior: Warn on Try->Except(Exception)->Pass
Configurable: Force typed exceptions Try->Except(Thing)->Pass to have documentation explaining why.'}, {'account_id': 11716, 'date': '2015-07-10 10:49:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Workflow-1

OK, i'll make the test configurable based on typed exceptions vs "Exception". Thanks for the input so far everyone, this has been a good discussion.'}, {'account_id': 11861, 'date': '2015-07-13 14:04:48.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

I'm not sure configurable is required here.  Inclusion of the test is already optional for projects that define their own profile.

For projects that include the profile, I think using #nosec to annotate an except+pass is a viable solution."}, {'account_id': 11716, 'date': '2015-07-14 12:11:33.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 6.'}, {'account_id': 11716, 'date': '2015-07-14 12:13:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

can now optionally ignore typed exception blocks. Exception is not considered typed'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-07-14 12:28:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Verified+1

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- gate-bandit-python34 http://logs.openstack.org/82/199582/6/check/gate-bandit-python34/a971ba2/ : SUCCESS in 47s
- gate-bandit-pep8 http://logs.openstack.org/82/199582/6/check/gate-bandit-pep8/688d4c6/ : SUCCESS in 23s
- gate-bandit-python27 http://logs.openstack.org/82/199582/6/check/gate-bandit-python27/2ca9d38/ : SUCCESS in 20s'}, {'account_id': 11029, 'date': '2015-07-14 15:10:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Code-Review+2

Looks good, thanks Tim.

(Side note - I ran into https://bugs.launchpad.net/testrepository/+bug/1229445 while running the py34 tox tests locally - workaround noted on the ticket worked for me, did not investigate further.)'}, {'account_id': 11716, 'date': '2015-07-14 15:33:59.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

interesting, thanks for letting me know Jamie. I havnt't seen that myself"}, {'account_id': 12000, 'date': '2015-07-14 17:12:10.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

I'm not confident this check will work on Python 3. There's only one Abstract Grammar Object (Try [1]) on Python 3.4 and that has the signature of

    Try(stmt* body, excepthandler* handlers, stmt* orelse, stmt* finalbody)

I think it will work, but I think we should check it a bit rigorously to just be safe.

(In other words, I've already forgotten if I papered over this or not when I added Python 3 compatibility.)

[1]: https://docs.python.org/3.4/library/ast.html?highlight=ast#abstract-grammar"}, {'account_id': 11716, 'date': '2015-07-14 17:46:40.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

Good point Ian. I wasn't 100% sure over Py3 compatibility my self, so I checked over the AST details, it should work correctly as written. Py3 AST still has ExceptionHandler nodes that work the same as Py2, this is supported by the fact that our Py34 gate hasn't exploded as well :)"}, {'account_id': 12000, 'date': '2015-07-14 18:45:22.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6: Code-Review+2

You're right Tim. I just did a quick check of the structure of the AST in Python 2.7 and 3.4 and they're pretty much identical. I'm just a bit ... paranoid. ;)"}, {'account_id': 12000, 'date': '2015-07-14 18:50:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Workflow+1

Forgot to approve this.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-07-14 18:50:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: -Verified

Starting gate jobs.
http://status.openstack.org/zuul/'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-07-14 18:59:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Verified+2

commit_message:
Adding test for Try, Except, Pass

Ignoring errors is bad in general, you should at least log it. This
is a security problem as increased exceptions from a service may
indicate attempts to break/fuzz it.

Change-Id: I8f6ad98a3f3dccb89d15f2e50beeaf4ce093323a

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-08-20 09:23:17.000000000', 'message': 'BGP Dynamic Routing: introduce routing instance

This is the first patch to provide BGP dynamic routing functionality in
Neutron.

Basic new entity for BGP is the RoutingInstance, to define from Neutron API
the upstream peers to exchange routes and the routes to advertise. This
patch provides a new extension ("dynamic_routing") with the basic CRUD
functionality to manage routing instances.

Note that new entities are created, such as RoutingPeers and
AdvertiseRoute (which extends from common Route entity), but both have a
relationship n-to-1 to RoutingInstance and are exposed through the
routing instance endpoint.

Binding between RoutingInstance and Router has been added too: the
router will 'learn' the discovered paths from defined routing peers.

Change-Id: I33e039df1bdd14af9ab83d9120595adc4ab2f38e
Partially-Implements: blueprint bgp-dynamic-routing

'}, {'created': '2015-06-28 16:35:52.000000000', 'message': '[WIP] BGP Dynamic Routing: introduce entities and model

This is the first patch to provide BGP dynamic route
advertisement functionality in Neutron.

This patch provides a new extension ("bgp_speaker") with
support for basic CRUD on bgp_speaker and bgp_peer, as
well as bgp_speaker-bgp_peer and bgp_speaker-network
bindings.

An admin user can create BgpSpeakers and configure
peering entities (BgpPeers) for BgpSpeakers. BgpSpeaker
to BgpPeer association is n-to-n. An admin user can
also associate networks with BgpSpeakers. Relationship
between BgpSpeaker and Network is 1-to-n.

This patch provides BGP-related functionality only to
admin users.

Change-Id: I33e039df1bdd14af9ab83d9120595adc4ab2f38e
Partially-Implements: blueprint bgp-dynamic-routing
Co-Authored-By: Ryan Tidwell <ryan.tidwell@hp.com>
Co-Authored-By: Jaume Devesa <devvesa@gmail.com>

commit_message:
[WIP] BGP Dynamic Routing: introduce entities and model

This is the first patch to provide BGP dynamic route
advertisement functionality in Neutron.
This patch provides a new extension ("bgp_speaker") with
support for basic CRUD on bgp_speaker and bgp_peer, as
well as bgp_speaker-bgp_peer and bgp_speaker-network
bindings.
An admin user can create BgpSpeakers and configure
peering entities (BgpPeers) for BgpSpeakers. BgpSpeaker
to BgpPeer association is n-to-n. An admin user can
also associate networks with BgpSpeakers. Relationship
between BgpSpeaker and Network is 1-to-n.
This patch provides BGP-related functionality only to
admin users.

Change-Id: I33e039df1bdd14af9ab83d9120595adc4ab2f38e
Partially-Implements: blueprint bgp-dynamic-routing
Co-Authored-By: Ryan Tidwell <ryan.tidwell@hp.com>
Co-Authored-By: Jaume Devesa <devvesa@gmail.com>
Co-Authored-By: Vikram Choudhary <vikram.choudhary@huawei.com>

commit_message:
Port dothill to Python 3

* Replace urllib2 with six.moves.urllib
* On Python 3, encode string to UTF-8 to hash it using MD5
* On Python 3, decode base64 from ASCII to get Unicode
* Replace "pattern in exc" with "pattern in exc.args"
* test_initialize_connection(): fix get_active_iscsi_target_portals()
  mock. Use the return_value attribute to return a dictionary, instead
  of returning a single IP address.
* tox.ini: add cinder.tests.unit.test_dothill to Python 3.4

Blueprint cinder-python3
Change-Id: Ib20bca813c2352eae447c374ded75c6dafb2e18d

commit_message:
Use keystone-juno package on Fuel Master node

  Keystone package on master node will not be updated
  to Kilo version. Original Juno Keystone package can probably
  conflict with Kilo dependencies on master node, that's why
  we are using keystone package with virtualenv. Only this
  package should be installed on master node.

  Related-bug: #1469552

Change-Id: I372be52a5764b1513f93f920b50615a657763a45

commit_message:
Drop XML support in Magnum

This patch disables XML from the Magnum API. It's modeled after
a simliar Ironic patch found here:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/169643/8.

To disable XML, we wrap wsmeext.pecan.expose() and replace all the
decorators with a call to magnum.api.expose.expose().

Change-Id: I53ee0ac4fa4a5d899d40cb87213e48ae84ec4970
Closes-bug: 1471507

commit_message:
Don't update floating IP status if no change

The floating IP status was going through all of the
status update code every time the L3 agent sent in
an update, even if the status didn't change.

This patch skips sending updates to the server if the
agent doesn't change the status.

Conflicts:
	neutron/agent/l3/agent.py
	neutron/agent/l3/router_info.py
	neutron/tests/unit/agent/l3/test_agent.py
	neutron/tests/unit/agent/l3/test_router_info.py

Change-Id: Ic3736bed3dc3e4ccb91f4acfabbf033949e09ce0
Partial-Bug: #1445412
(cherry picked from commit c44506bfd60b2dd6036e113464f1ea682cfaeb6c)

commit_message:
Close DB migration sessions explicitly for compatibility with PyMySQL

oslo.db lib starting with version 1.12.0 uses PyMySQL as mysql client.
We get problem with it as it does not close opened sessions by default.
And if we do some actions with migration sessions and do not close sessions,
then alembic, as db migration tool does not write to DB updated migration
version, that is final step of each migration.
It breaks further attempts to perform some migration actions in case some
migration can not be applied twice. Because of improper versions in DB,
alembic tries to execute same migrations again and again.

So, close migration sessions explicitly since PyMySQL does not do it itself.
Also, print version in devstack for getting more details in future debug of
devstack installation output.

Change-Id: I5c729f10bac23b1853e18127b50b1d9f053ab629
Closes-Bug: #1473400

commit_message:
Redis Clustering

Outlines the implementation of the clustering API for the Redis
database.  It is expected that implementing this blueprint will
consist primarily of implementing existing APIs for the experimental
Redis datastore.

Change-Id: I44a9a256ed6922cf85e0328080292f3376d1f5d1
Implements: blueprint redis-cluster

commit_message:
Always use gate- instead of check- (f-k*)

Change pipeline name to only use "gate", we do not need the
differentiation between check and gate anymore.

This changes the pipelines configured via files in jenkins/jobs/[f-k]*.

Change-Id: I4452141ad9ce0bb5e429d9d0e1a3e37c8303fb25

commit_message:
Fix failures related to the mock 1.1.0 release

The functional gate is also failing due to a recent
change introduced in devstack -> I613f1bdc6673f0c4bfe29aaab7b514348a617a8c

This fixes both the gates, functional and unit tests.

Co-Authored-By: Thomas Herve <therve@redhat.com>
Closes-Bug: #1473398
Change-Id: Ia77a1fd884c6346edfb90777e91a51d279ccd92a
(cherry picked from commit 3216f6126f0c0c61eb9ae0016fb9dd1df15e5500)

To be able to later make the onSharedStorage parameter of the evacuate
API optional first we have to make the on_shared_storage parameter of
the rebuild_instance optional in the compute manager.

After this modification if the on_shared_storage is not provided then
the rebuild_instance call will use the instance_on_disk function of
the virt dirver to decide if the instance files need to be recreated or

Implements: bp optional-on-shared-storage-flag-in-rebuild-instance
Change-Id: I4217bd00d8c253db522241885dba2847a26af6df
'}]
commit_message:
Make on_shared_storage optional in compute manager

To be able to later make the onSharedStorage parameter of the evacuate
API optional first we have to make the on_shared_storage parameter of
the rebuild_instance optional in the compute manager.

After this modification if the on_shared_storage is not provided then
the rebuild_instance call will use the instance_on_disk function of
the virt dirver to decide if the instance files need to be recreated or
they can be reused.

Implements: bp optional-on-shared-storage-flag-in-rebuild-instance
Change-Id: I4217bd00d8c253db522241885dba2847a26af6df

commit_message:
Make NoValidHost exceptions clearer

Adds the MaxRetriesExceeded exception class as a subclass of
NoValidHost, and changes the exceptions raised in those cases to the
more specific MaxRetriesExceeded. Also added an informative comment to a
previously empty NoValidHost exception in the spirit of improving the
reporting of these failures.

Change-Id: I286a215504ed5af8779d6a4d9249842633f47f50
Partially-Implements: blueprint: no-valid-host-reporting

commit_message:
libvirt: update volume delete snapshot to use Guest

This commit updates the method _volume_delete_snapshot
to make it pass a Guest object and then use a
BlockDevice object to deal with block device operations

Change-Id: Ibd2296109696cbd62292b5c68e038e2b58e7519c

I'm starting to think this was not a well thought out idea. The bug itself, just describes the fact that the checks were removed from upstream, but does not mention why they were removed, and why we want them back.

http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2014-December/052519.html this ML thread covers really well why these checks are dangerous.

Could you please update the bug (and probably this commits commit message) to include info on why we need this back. Links to ML threads are appreciated.

Furthermore — I do not like the idea of adding 400+ LOC of foreign and seemingly unsupported code to our code base. If there is a plan for this code to be removed in future (say when the checks are going to be returned to upstream hacking) — it should be noted either in commit message or in readme (or both)

I want to block it, before I have a clear understanding on why we're doing this and whether we should. We could also discuss this during IRC meeting or you can contact me, to clear things out (as I might not be seeing the whole picture)

I also feel, that I should apologise, cause I initially supported the idea, but changed my mind since then."}, {'account_id': 7535, 'date': '2015-07-13 05:47:57.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

PowerVM now allows a uuid to be set at LPAR create time. The

commit_message:
Set PowerVM uuid to OpenStack uuid

PowerVM now allows a uuid to be set at LPAR create time. The
uuid formats are not exactly the same (they differ by a single
bit) but the OpenStack uuid can be converted to a PowerVM uuid
and used at spawn time.

PowerVM uuid format always has the most significant bit set to 0.

Change-Id: I041397047f413b5142ee6b7537ad60a3c396cc80

commit_message:
Moved js-yaml to dependencies.

The index.js script which imports our eslint configuration requires
that js-yaml be accessible, however it was not included in the
project's dependencies. This moves it from devDependencies (installed
during packaging) to dependencies (installed always).

Change-Id: I7f7b0967b86f5312f5801fb4dbfbe72a453583aa

commit_message:
Add missing options to Ceilometer/Ironic/Horizon

Backend options for Ceilometer and Ironic are aligned with what we
use for the other OpenStack services.

Listener options for Horizon is updated so that we do cookie
tracking as suggested by refarch doc.

Change-Id: I4640d974a3ab8188919eaae79dde71463234b5ff

'}, {'created': '2015-06-19 22:01:02.000000000', 'message': 'Implement SSL keys generation

Keys generated in astute prehook and saved in master
node for further use. In current implementation only
one key for haproxy generated and then it will used
for all public OpenStack URLs.
If self-signed certificates created then new astute
prehook task added will copy that certificates to
apropriate nodes.

Also this change add new ssl modular task that checks
if user uploaded certificate exists and saves it from
yaml to local node filesystem.

Cross-Depend on: I2261dcfb55743b0fb31f4cbe42e7793176c8e1c0

commit_message:
Implement SSL keys generation

Keys are generated in astute prehook and saved in master
node for further use. In current implementation only
one key for haproxy is generated and then it will be used
for all public OpenStack URLs.
If self-signed certificates are created then new astute
prehook task added will copy those certificates to
apropriate nodes.

Also this change adds new ssl modular task that checks
if user uploaded certificate exists and saves it from
yaml to local node filesystem.

Implements: blueprint ssl-endpoints
Depends-On: I2261dcfb55743b0fb31f4cbe42e7793176c8e1c0
Change-Id: Ifcd9194b51129ea262363196a9963a96cc5760bb

commit_message:
Modify confusing name in Huawei driver

Modify "share_type" to "share_url_type" in Huawei driver,
because "share type" is used in Manila for different thing.

Change-Id: I4b51b3a3cd0cc2e9ee36bcf9953a3bee1f4f4fa8
Closes-Bug: #1469361

commit_message:
Modifying Paramiko Injection plugin

The way the paramiko check was previously working didn't catch
many uses because the qualified name is difficult to predict for
Paramiko calls.  This commit changes it so that paramiko detection
is accomplished by the combination of importing paramiko and using
one of the paramiko functions that executes with a shell.

Change-Id: Ib6e8f596a8f05475213be0ac8cf27e4e308b9617

commit_message:
Link bindep documentation in the infra index

This adds a link to the bindep documentation, but should not be
approved until such documentation is successfully published by the
parent change so as to avoid creating a broken hyperlink in the
meantime.

Change-Id: If1e65725d2134ba1b299ab89a729f1638e529e82

commit_message:
Add networking-lenovo project to OpenStack.

This repo will be used for the development of backend ML2 mech drivers
and service plugins for Lenovo networking products.

Related governance change: I0acf7a87ff2ee67ace9468f479e78754d0be1572
Change-Id: Ie61cda0fa58d7e1c4c0c8fd1a7cdbca474b28af4

Refactor pulling translations into a common func

In preperation for switching projects one at a time to pulling
translations from Zanata, refactor the two calls to tx pull into
a common function.

commit_message:
Add check-requirements job to openstack/anchor

Previously requirements for openstack/anchor were
handled outside of global-requirements.  This change
adds a the check-requirement job, which enforces
global-requirements compliance.

Partial-Bug: #1472540
Signed-off-by: Dave Walker (Daviey) <email@daviey.com>
Change-Id: Ieac0a525919a3499b9af4990564120ff169ac098

temporarily skip help tests

We're trying to change cliff for the better, by improving the UX
of the help command. But cliff tests against the tip of OSC.

Temporarily skip the tests that are failing and then update them
once the fix for cliff has been merged.

The patch in question: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/201258/

[{'created': '2015-07-14 14:43:49.000000000', 'message': "Use an Anchor when service is managed

Today, Keystone resources (domains, tenants, etc) are created only if
'keystone' service is started.
When running Keystone in WSGI, the autorequire is broken for those
resources.
Adding 'httpd' in autorequire is not enough because it could fail to
orchestration issues if running another httpd resource (Horizon) that
depends on having Keystone started.

This patch is about to create an Anchor (keystone_started) in
keystone::service that require Service['keystone'] resource to be
created.
In resource types, change the autorequire to depend on the new Anchor.

With that patch, we are sure Keystone resources won't be created before
service is actually managed (running or stopped) and other resources
(Horizon, using httpd server) can also depend on this Anchor if needed.

Change-Id: Ie72b65b6be224cadc8730e050bec38d2face5dfd
Closes-bug: #1474059
(cherry picked from commit c11b0408ef0f2d98749106cabc47c7d0b9268b4c)
"}]
commit_message:
Use an Anchor when service is managed

Today, Keystone resources (domains, tenants, etc) are created only if
'keystone' service is started.
When running Keystone in WSGI, the autorequire is broken for those
resources.
Adding 'httpd' in autorequire is not enough because it could fail to
orchestration issues if running another httpd resource (Horizon) that
depends on having Keystone started.

This patch is about to create an Anchor (keystone_started) in
keystone::service that require Service['keystone'] resource to be
created.
In resource types, change the autorequire to depend on the new Anchor.

With that patch, we are sure Keystone resources won't be created before
service is actually managed (running or stopped) and other resources
(Horizon, using httpd server) can also depend on this Anchor if needed.

Change-Id: Ie72b65b6be224cadc8730e050bec38d2face5dfd
Closes-bug: #1474059
(cherry picked from commit c11b0408ef0f2d98749106cabc47c7d0b9268b4c)

commit_message:
nodepool: describe nodepool-base env variables

The nodepool-base element relies on a couple environement variables.
Describe NODEPOOL_SCRIPTDIR and NODEPOOL_STATIC_NAMESERVER in the
README.rst file.

commit_message:
Move experimental Manila jobs in Rally to check pipeline

CI jobs 'gate-rally-dsvm-manila-multibackend' and
'gate-rally-dsvm-manila-multibackend-no-ss' for Rally project are stable, so
move them to check pipeline.

Change-Id: If7251cac99695576364e33be397303bce70edb4f

commit_message:
Allowing job binary objects to be updated

Job Binary objects can now be updated as long as they
are not referenced by an active job in the PENDING state.

Change-Id: I9e1559e3ab5ff07557f284ae59bb8161591b6e6c
Implements: bp edp-edit-job-binaries

commit_message:
Add project fuel-nailgun-agent repo

Before this we kept node discovery agent
in stackforge/fuel-web repo:

* https://github.com/stackforge/fuel-web/blob/master/bin/agent
* https://github.com/stackforge/fuel-web/blob/master/bin/nailgun-agent.cron

I am suggesting to move it because:

* written on Ruby instead of Python;
* installed on nodes unlike Nailgun;
* it is client for Nailgun API;
* need another core-reviewers team;
* need to be tested differently.

We kept changes history from fuel-web repository
Closes-Bug: #1473893

There don't seem to be any existing test cases specifically for the extension loading code, although select_extensions gets tested as a side effect of testing most of the individual extensions. So I'm not sure where to put such a test case.

Would it make sense instead to merge this as-is, and then for me to file a follow-up bug (and assign it to myself) to write unit tests for all of the extension loading stuff?"}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2015-03-12 18:47:37.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

just because there aren't existing unit tests for this bit of code doesn't mean we shouldn't make sure this new change has unit test coverage.

Also note: this all changes when we move forward to v2.1"}, {'account_id': 11748, 'date': '2015-03-12 18:53:37.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I agree. So:

1) Would it be reasonable to merge this as-is and add tests for all of the extension loaders in a subsequent commit, which I would take on?

2) If not, where should the test(s) for the new loader go?

I'm happy to write tests either way, as I said in my last comment, I just need some guidance on the best way to proceed."}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2015-03-12 18:56:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

New patchset including a first crack at tests. In order to avoid an extensive and borderline absurd mocking setup, I just created a set of dummy extensions to load (and I do mean "dummy"). Hope this approach works for people.

I did run into one strange behavior that may be a bug: the include/exclude lists are not consulted when loading extensions that aren't just simple files, but instead are whole packages themselves. Nova compute doesn't currently include any such extensions, but something to be aware of in the future, and perhaps deserving of its own bug.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-03-16 19:40:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

commit_message:
Allow blacklisting os-api extensions

Currently os-api extensions can only be disabled by choosing which
ones to enable. With nearly a hundred extensions, disabling a single
extension is absurdly onerous. This makes it possible to blacklist
extensions as well by adding a new osapi_compute_extension loader,
nova.api.openstack.compute.contrib.exclude_extensions, which can be
used in concord with osapi_compute_ext_list to disable extensions.

This also adds unit tests for many of the extension loading bits.

DocImpact
Closes-Bug: 1427838
Change-Id: I4d3047bb36e02cfda87749cb1225d7c2f851a7fa

Looks good so far.  As you mention in the commit message you're going to need to save the BDM for the "attach during spawn" flow.  It's not passed into the volume driver (vscsi) are you going to change it so it will be passed in, or save it after the fact in the spawn flow?'}, {'account_id': 8190, 'date': '2015-07-08 21:33:38.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

TBH - I'm currently debating the best place to do the save.

I see two options.  The obvious is as you mentioned - as part of the spawn.

The second is that I could embed it into the task.  But I'm not sure I like the logic that would produce.  Since at that point, you only have the connection_info I would need to get the volume_id - connection_info['volume_id'].  From that I could look up the block_device and then swap in my new connection info, and run the save on the block device.

The second method is more thorough.  With multiple volumes, that might be a good approach...

If you have some thoughts on which you think is the better approach, let me know!"}, {'account_id': 13562, 'date': '2015-07-09 11:34:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

After looking the code over, including looking at the manager shutdown instance, detach volume, terminate flows, I think the best place to do the save is in the for loop here: https://github.com/stackforge/nova-powervm/blob/master/nova_powervm/virt/powervm/driver.py#L235

That would make nova-powervm match how the manager and libvirt virt driver do this and would avoid an unnecessary save and its related DB overhead in the "attach after spawn" flow.

Another note, it is currently unnecessary to unset the UDID in the terminate connection flow.  When volumes are detached from a VM or the VM is destroyed, the BDM object is also destroyed making it unnecessary to update the connection info object in the BDM before the whole thing is destroyed anyway.  The only time you'd want to update the connection info in the DB for a disconnect operation and not delete the whole BDM is in a spawn failure-reschedule scenario to avoid connection info leaking from one host to another.  This should be handled by the manager but I think it currently has bugs in this area.  Regardless, the blanking of BDM connection info before a reschedule should be a manager  handled function since it knows whether or not a reschedule will be attempted.'}, {'account_id': 8190, 'date': '2015-07-09 11:49:57.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I'm also thinking that the terminate connection flow, removing the metadata out of the BDM would be a bad idea.  If you're using shared volumes that could cause an issue where a detach from one VM could remove metadata for the second BDM as well.

It made sense when the metadata was stored on the instance itself.  But in moving to the BDM model, I don't think it does.

Will update that in a revision as well."}, {'account_id': 8190, 'date': '2015-07-09 12:00:09.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Since it is a mapping, it is one BDM per volume per instance.  So shared volume support won't be impacted if we left the code in to remove the UDID key.

Still doesn't add value.  Will look to remove it."}, {'account_id': 8190, 'date': '2015-07-09 12:41:04.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 8190, 'date': '2015-07-09 12:43:23.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-07-09 12:55:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified+1

commit_message:
Move disk UUID to BDM

The vSCSI volume connector requires that the disk UUID be saved on the
instance so that it can be discovered correctly for the removal
operation.  This had been done on the instance's system metadata.  This
change set moves it onto the BDM.

Change-Id: I8a242a3397e04757a5551c22b03017f095f34625
Closes-Bug: 1471847

commit_message:
Adding Kuryr as a part of neutron big stadium.

Kuryr aims to service the Docker Container Network Model[1]  by leveraging
Neutron in a way similar to how Nova does.

The project will serve as a single effort point for connecting
the various Neutron sub projects with Dockers and provide
different Docker plumbing (connecting the docker instances into
the overlay) images for the various different Neutron plugins
and implementations

[1] https://github.com/docker/docker/blob/master/experimental/networking.md

Change-Id: I38f24906493e25575b084b06b7a62bbfc0c2f414

commit_message:
Policy Based Modification of Environment

Goal is to be able to define modification of an environment by Congress policies prior
deployment. This allows to add components (for example monitoring), change/set properties
(for example to enforce given zone, flavors, ...) and relationships into environment,
so modified environment is after that deployed.

Change-Id: I37d7dbfad351e42c89db2d5fd82d4f08581a040c

commit_message:
Fix set_default() when used before config init

Using set_default() before initializing OpenStackConfig would cause
an error since the _defaults dict would still be None and not an
actual dict. This corrects that by calling get_defaults() to make
sure it is initialized properly, and also adds a warning to note
that the method is now deprecated.

Change-Id: I81803c680b614f9bee47c6f69a4efffa638dcebc

[{'created': '2015-07-08 23:24:33.000000000', 'message': "Raise minimum python-openstackclient to 1.4.0

OSC commit 224d375ef4120998dc51fbf55f1778d1ccf118a0 added the --wait
option to the `openstack server delete` command which we want to use in
grenade, so we need to raise the minimum required version to 1.4.0.

We won't be able to actually use --wait in grenade until the M release
where stable/liberty would have this minimum required version for the
option.

Related grenade change: I16981765c12db7145f7c4754d454431afb6d5cbb

Related-Bug: #1460112

Change-Id: If488b664cb4f137fdbbacf902d56912d5908aa3b
"}]
commit_message:
Raise minimum python-openstackclient to 1.4.0

OSC commit 224d375ef4120998dc51fbf55f1778d1ccf118a0 added the --wait
option to the `openstack server delete` command which we want to use in
grenade, so we need to raise the minimum required version to 1.4.0.

We won't be able to actually use --wait in grenade until the M release
where stable/liberty would have this minimum required version for the
option.

Related grenade change: I16981765c12db7145f7c4754d454431afb6d5cbb

Related-Bug: #1460112

Change-Id: If488b664cb4f137fdbbacf902d56912d5908aa3b

commit_message:
Don't change undisclosed param on slave-change

If use only one of --vcpu or --ram param in slave-change command,
      other param won't use default value and won't change VM

Change-Id: Ie1e37d1083a1f860d1b03d8c75af3500201c2f67
Closes-bug: #1464649

commit_message:
Disable instance with file creation if ceph is use

In kilo files injection is disabled if ceph is using,
so  that we need display tests only for
deployments without ceph

Related-Bug: #1473164

commit_message:
Fix policy.json certificate_authority inconsistency

Change the certificate_authority add_to_project, remove_from_project,
and set_preferred entries to use rule:admin instead of role:admin. This
brings these entries into consistency with their neighbors.

Closes-Bug: #1473593
Change-Id: Ibdb7512cf751b92298e350dac1689b036a6fd023

commit_message:
Fix false positive result for file injection

Raise exception if 'False' is result of
command execution.
Also check if there is not 'ping' i the command raise
message different then "Instance connectivity issue"

Change-Id: I38bb7be403d73a262a33def79476fd844ae4c06d
Closes-Bug: #1473164

commit_message:
fuel-agent: use different md metadata version

0.90 will be used for centos only letting GRUB-legacy to boot.
Otherwise, default (1.2) will be used as GRUB2 is able to deal with it.

Change-Id: I89c5178d991970de4682c1e239e0ecb014ba61bd
Closes-Bug: #1430432

commit_message:
Remove haproxy galera monitoring user

Prior to kilo, we created a static 'haproxy' MySQL user for haproxy.
In kilo and onwards, we now have a user variable called
galera_monitoring_user which defaults to monitoring.  This commit
updates scripts/run-upgrade.sh to remove the old haproxy user to
ensure we don't have a defunct MySQL user lying about.

Change-Id: I071596c4c6d881d5304fc49a7cf752d5489ee19b
Closes-Bug: #1472673
(cherry picked from commit c51aaaccac3fca5cc202c7784ecb9f7a9490d5d0)

commit_message:
Adding Angular Project Images Panel

This patch creates a blank Images panel in the project dashboard.

It follows the pattern established by the following merged commits:

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/190865/
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/190852/

Dependent patches will be added for:
 - index table
 - forms
 - actions

Change-Id: I2fe5492c3954aa8c1ed751d062d22f0fe8c5f3d1
Partially-Implements: blueprint angularize-images-table

commit_message:
Allow galera wsrep_provider_options to be customised

This patch introduces galera_wsrep_provider_options as a list of
options instead of only catering for changing the gcache.size
option. This allows the deployer to change any number of the
wsrep_provider_options available.

Note: The variable galera_gcache_size is respected in this patch
but if galera_wsrep_provider_options is customised by a deployer
then the custom list must include reference to galera_gcache_size
for it to be respected.

DocImpact
Closes-Bug: #1464699
Co-Authored-By: Ian Cordasco <ian.cordasco@rackspace.com>
Change-Id: I78a5a1d344729fdc06636b1c6dade63a7ba59e94
(cherry picked from commit 999fc102d11fc64d7140b87e1a246bb196b44f39)

[{'created': '2015-07-13 14:09:08.000000000', 'message': 'Add role system-crontab-coordination

Currently every host, both containers and bare metal, has a crontab
configured with the same values for minute, hour, day of week etc. This
means that there is the potential for a service interruption if, for
example, a cron job were to cause a service to restart.

This commit adds a new role which attempts to adjust the times defined
in the entries in the default /etc/crontab to reduce the overlap
between hosts.

Closes-bug: #1424705

'}]
commit_message:
Add role system-crontab-coordination

Currently every host, both containers and bare metal, has a crontab
configured with the same values for minute, hour, day of week etc. This
means that there is the potential for a service interruption if, for
example, a cron job were to cause a service to restart.

This commit adds a new role which attempts to adjust the times defined
in the entries in the default /etc/crontab to reduce the overlap
between hosts.

Change-Id: I18bf0ac0c0610283a19c40c448ac8b6b4c8fd8f5
Closes-bug: #1424705
(cherry picked from commit e148635e789568a2c886c3a669884bd0d82d9a72)

commit_message:
Fixing mistral resources path

 * Fixed standard actions and workflows paths.
   If mistral is installed in system, 'resources'
   are not copied to dist-packages/mistral, so
   mistral-db-manage populate command won't work.
   Now resources are included in mistral.

Closes-Bug: #1457842

Change-Id: I3149867e615acd188691b299a051e7458e2eb386
(cherry picked from commit 4e699ce21b467cae3000cebfa3b4c2cdbfc05441)

commit_message:
Always use gate- instead of check (akanda, ceilometer)

Remove extra pipeline parameter and only use "gate", we do not need the
differentiation between check and gate anymore.

Change-Id: Id6e8074d81759285b6acb957343123dd306f43e8

[{'created': '2015-07-13 19:14:08.000000000', 'message': "Use an Anchor when service is managed

Today, Keystone resources (domains, tenants, etc) are created only if
'keystone' service is started.
When running Keystone in WSGI, the autorequire is broken for those
resources.
Adding 'httpd' in autorequire is not enough because it could fail to
orchestration issues if running another httpd resource (Horizon) that
depends on having Keystone started.

This patch is about to create an Anchor (keystone_started) in
keystone::service that require Service['keystone'] resource to be
created.
In resource types, change the autorequire to depend on the new Anchor.

With that patch, we are sure Keystone resources won't be created before
service is actually managed (running or stopped) and other resources
(Horizon, using httpd server) can also depend on this Anchor if needed.

Change-Id: Ie72b65b6be224cadc8730e050bec38d2face5dfd

commit_message:
Use an Anchor when service is managed

Today, Keystone resources (domains, tenants, etc) are created only if
'keystone' service is started.
When running Keystone in WSGI, the autorequire is broken for those
resources.
Adding 'httpd' in autorequire is not enough because it could fail to
orchestration issues if running another httpd resource (Horizon) that
depends on having Keystone started.

This patch is about to create an Anchor (keystone_started) in
keystone::service that require Service['keystone'] resource to be
created.
In resource types, change the autorequire to depend on the new Anchor.

With that patch, we are sure Keystone resources won't be created before
service is actually managed (running or stopped) and other resources
(Horizon, using httpd server) can also depend on this Anchor if needed.

Change-Id: Ie72b65b6be224cadc8730e050bec38d2face5dfd
Closes-bug: #1474059

commit_message:
Remove usage of dict.iterkeys()

Replace "for key in dict.iterkeys()" with "for key in dict"; make
congress python-3 compatible

Change-Id: Id2478fc6e315d0742909d54dbc15adbc9ba41b0f
Partially-Implements: blueprint support-python3

commit_message:
[Launch Instance Fix] Smart-Table Client Side Magic Search

Directives to allow use of Magic Search with Smart-Table.
Only client side filtering is available in this patch.

Current implemented in the "Select Soure" step in the
Launch Instane workflow. Implementation in other steps
to follow.

Tests to follow also.

Co-Authored-By: Randy Bertram <rbertram@us.ibm.com>
Co-Authored-By: Aaron Sahlin <asahlin@us.ibm.com>

Change-Id: I94fd4c1ebe4e791b30146863c4a06843b4e70dcb
Closes-Bug: #1434710

commit_message:
bump python-openstack client to 1.5.0

python-openstackclient 1.0.3 does not work with master because there
is a massive set of conflicts between master requirements and the
capped requirements on the 1.0.x branch. Bump to the latest release to
reflect something closer to reality.

Change-Id: I6e4a22df38ceb82a85a7156bb2236c559002de17

I've commented (and asked some quick questions) inline. Still need some feedback on what to say about Mesos/marathon.

As for breaking this up, I'm in favor of NOT multiplying the work by somehow dividing this up. The docs need updating, and the fact that this is now a virtual overhaul is a bonus. No living, iterating document is ever "done", and there will certainly be further changes and tweaks in time. I appreciate the constructive feedback as always, and will update accordingly, but the end goal is to get this published so we can have a new foundation to build on and further refine, while allowing people to benefit from these updates as we go.'}, {'account_id': 7494, 'date': '2015-07-10 08:09:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

I also prefer split this to several patches.'}, {'account_id': 668, 'date': '2015-07-10 15:33:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

With respect to previous comments, normally keeping reviews to a single topic is our best practice, but documentation may be an exception because some changes we really need to see in context. 

I would also like to remind our reviewers to help merge iterative improvements. If we can merge something better that we currently have, that could make a meaningful difference for a newcomer to understand our software.

Please ask yourself "what harm will come if we merge this?". If we are making an improvement, even if it is not perfect, let's make that our preference. If we can make it better with a -1 vote in a way that will not be burdensome for the contributor, then we should. If we want to ask for something major in a -1 vote, let's consider merging the proposed patch as a first iteration, and filing a tech debt bug against it for future improvement. This way we get improvements in small increments, helping more of us sooner.'}, {'account_id': 668, 'date': '2015-07-10 15:42:21.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

When we received a remote exception from a nested stack, we were modifying
the formatting string of the exception's class in the mistaken belief that
copy.copy() makes copies of classes. Use a subclass instead, so that future
exceptions of the same type raised locally use the correct formatting string.

Change-Id: I43fcce4758848f6388b9d6da68a121c04a68f5cb
Closes-Bug: #1474153
"}]
commit_message:
Don't modify exception formatting strings

When we received a remote exception from a nested stack, we were modifying
the formatting string of the exception's class in the mistaken belief that
copy.copy() makes copies of classes. Use a subclass instead, so that future
exceptions of the same type raised locally use the correct formatting string.

Change-Id: I43fcce4758848f6388b9d6da68a121c04a68f5cb
Closes-Bug: #1474153

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-07-13 16:57:51.000000000', 'message': 'fuel-agent: do not use lazy umount

Using "umount -l" is a potentially dangerous act as
fuel-agent doesn't wait until any process stops using files
on that mounted fs.

Use of lazy umount should be disabled by default.
In case if regular umount failed,
it means abnormal sutiation where manual intervention is needed as
lazy umount couldn't sort out the issue by itself.

Change-Id: If258535c43402142a8dcad0c87bc519fcc6904d2
Closes-Bug: #1454366
'}]
commit_message:
fuel-agent: do not use lazy umount

Using "umount -l" is a potentially dangerous act as
fuel-agent doesn't wait until any process stops using files
on that mounted fs.

Use of lazy umount should be disabled by default.
In case if regular umount failed,
it means abnormal sutiation where manual intervention is needed as
lazy umount couldn't sort out the issue by itself.

Change-Id: If258535c43402142a8dcad0c87bc519fcc6904d2
Closes-Bug: #1454366

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

    IRC: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/IRC

[{'created': '2015-07-03 11:54:58.000000000', 'message': 'Implements: blueprint multi-region-swift
Change-Id: I3c718ece6643fe932cb45bf5baea620c5c8a9408
'}, {'created': '2015-07-03 12:26:14.000000000', 'message': 'Multi-region swift

A Swift cluster can be deployed in such a way that the cluster spans
multiple geographically dispersed data centers. This allows an end-user
to ensure resiliency in the event of a data center failure, with one or
more copies of an object stored in each data center location. This
facilitates end-users being able to build out geographically dispersed
infrastructure, enabling high availability.

Implements: blueprint multi-region-swift
Change-Id: I3c718ece6643fe932cb45bf5baea620c5c8a9408
'}, {'created': '2015-07-07 15:50:05.000000000', 'message': 'Multi-region swift

commit_message:
Multi-region swift

A Swift cluster can be deployed in such a way that the cluster spans
multiple geographically dispersed data centers. This allows an end-user
to ensure resiliency in the event of a data center failure, with one or
more copies of an object stored in each data center location. This
facilitates end-users being able to build out geographically dispersed
infrastructure, enabling high availability.

Implements: blueprint multi-region-swift
Change-Id: I3c718ece6643fe932cb45bf5baea620c5c8a9408

commit_message:
Correct node override for experimental bindep job

This job doesn't have "dsvm" in the name, so zuul is calling
default_params_trusty() on it rather than devstack-params(). Correct
the functions to match this expectation.

Change-Id: I25e0e638d3d0dc1be66dfc8e17712ca995aa3a3a

commit_message:
Add tool for reporting Bandit OpenStack coverage

This script is intended for inclusion in the Bandit repository and usage
by the Bandit and other OpenStack teams.  It is not intended for inclusion
in Bandit packages / distribution.

It executes against Jenkins and Zuul configuration files in the
openstack-infra/project-config repository, parses out Bandit jobs
and tests, and prints a summary of results.

It includes definition of an openstack_coverage testenv in tox.ini with
basic PyYAML and request dependencies to allow easy venv creation and
script execution.

Co-Authored-By: Ian Cordasco <graffatcolmingov@gmail.com>
Change-Id: I2d133146223a6b185347662b47cc2bd6355a0900

commit_message:
Make gate-keystone-python34 voting and add gate

Make the gate-keystone-python34 check job voting. Add also a voting
gate-keystone-python34 gate job by using the python3-jobs template.

The python34 job now pass, it's time to make it voting to avoid Python 3
regressions.

Change-Id: I51c18bc98bb5943d4c712c96216a12ee496783d4

Add BEAKER_color flag

A recent commit to beaker-rspec[1] added the ability to toggle color
output. So we disable colors to the console.

commit_message:
Add log rotation for docker containers

Run a cronjob which executes a command like:

  dockerctl shell CONTAINER logrotate /etc/logrotate.conf

This will allow logrotate to reload needed services using configs
shipped with the packages.

We aslo need to remove "rsyslog" and "nginx" packages from
containers that use "nailgun::packages" class to avoid logrotate
duplication. So we create a new class "nailgun::common" and use it
in our $service-only.pp manifests instead of "nailgun::packages"

Change-Id: Ic625e086db7bcd3622bce73ec4cec0dd6f81121d

Make gate-glance_store-python34 voting, add gate

Make the gate-glance_store-python34 check job voting by removing the
configuration making it non-voting.

python3-jobs.

commit_message:
Disable coredumps for centos by default

We do not ship debuginfo packages so debugging coredumps is not
very usefull anyway. If cloud operator/administrator wants to get
and analyze coredumps, he can easily enable them back at any time.
Uncontrolled coredump generation may lead to "disk full" errors
and thus break a lot of services and data.

poke ci
Change-Id: I57efc51bb81d930614e4651c8d056512b3e24275
Closes-bug: #1253577

commit_message:
Merge availability_zone tests between v2 and v2.1

Currently v2 and v2.1 have separate functional tests and their
corresponding sample files. As v2 and v2.1 are supposed to be identical,
there is overhead to maintain two set of functional tests and sample files.
We can have one set of tests which can run for both v2 and v2.1.

This commit merges availability_zone functional tests.

In V2.1 os-access-ip is separate plugin where in v2 it was mixed in server
plugin itself. So os-access-ip extension is enabled to run
merged functional tests for both v2 and v2.1.
Also enabling some required extension for v2 tests.

Change-Id: I82e7011da212cb4699c4c19b95523a54a6c2f259

commit_message:
Add image while launching instance from image(create new volumn)

In legacy launch instance, when launching instance from
image(create new volumn), we can not see image name in
instance table, the patch fix it.

Change-Id: I1b63dd739b60a1141d1666f06763eea6c056743d
Closes-Bug: #1460584

commit_message:
Add dependency on nodepool-base to node-devstack

The build for node-devstack will fail because of missing scripts unless
nodepool-base is executed before, so add this as dependency.

Change-Id: Iabc06a542529500ad248ae067beed9639d24e506

commit_message:
Ability to auto generate the filesystem store metadata file

After this path has been merged : https://review.openstack.org/#/c/190265/
The compute service has the ability to copy the image data from the mountpoint
directly which can save image download time.

This patch make the metadata file can be generated automatically if user
specify the id and mountpoint.

Change-Id: Ibd4cc2d15a97f8018fc7f0aa19e4f2c9d1da285c

- gate-neutron-specs-python27 http://logs.openstack.org/37/192937/3/check/gate-neutron-specs-python27/f47a82a/ : SUCCESS in 1m 35s'}, {'account_id': 7787, 'date': '2015-06-20 00:26:07.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

This has come to my attention because it's now blocking me from moving forward with a feature I'm working on (https://review.openstack.org/#/c/191707/).

If I understand this proposal correctly, I have to rewrite the code so that it works with either version of the schema. Additionally, it has to also work with a mix of the old and new schema (i.e. after expansion scripts are applied but before contraction scripts).

So I will need logic in the model that detects the presence of the old column; and, as long as it's present, rely on and update that instead of the new table. Additionally, all of the new features that rely on this table basically have to detect whether or not it is present and disable themselves while the column is missing.

Then the migration of the data from the old column to the new table will take place in the contraction script that drops the old column.

Did I get everything correctly?

If so, I have another question. How often should I be running detection for the presence of the old schema in my application logic? The logic in the model can't know until a query is issued to the DB, at which point an exception will be thrown on a missing column or table. Should we put a special decorator somewhere high up in the stack that catches schema errors that triggers all models to query the underlying DB to determine which schema to use?"}, {'account_id': 6524, 'date': '2015-06-20 01:00:11.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

I have to sympathize a little with Kevin here. Are we rushing ahead a little too quickly with imposing the new requirements on migrations? Before we impose them, should we perhaps first have in place a framework and utilities to ease the burden on Neutron developers?

I think it is reasonable to set a goal of L (or M if needed) release as the last point at which non-additive migrations are allowed. We tell users that they can't do online migrations until they have upgraded offline to L (or M)."}, {'account_id': 7787, 'date': '2015-06-20 01:14:05.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

I'm fine with making the changes if this is somewhat close to being done. What I want to avoid though is waiting until L3 to be able to move forward.

If I'm right about all of the logic this will entail on the application side, it would be much easier for me to leave the shared column on the networks table, skip the data migration and then just special-case wildcard shared networks in the new RBAC API to reference the old column."}, {'account_id': 11816, 'date': '2015-06-20 01:23:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Hi Kevin -

Well, you're hitting on the data migration issue that arises once the project decides that it has to support upgrading the schema while the app is still running.  As far as how that will go, I think it's too early to say exactly, and I thought in Ihar's thread on the list they were going for full OSM to happen by M, not necessarily L.    Let's just establish up front that the migration scripts themselves can be organized into an expand/contract model as described here *without* changing anything else about the approach.  We can still put data migrations in "expand" or "expand offline" scripts, it's just we aren't fully "online" ready at that point, but even then, the "expand" phase is still runnable while the old version of the app keeps running.   The proposal here is really just taking the same migrations we'd have anyway and just rearranging them a bit, and neutron can start with this part of it without going full "online" as of yet.    By maintaining the fact that migration scripts are in place, the movement to the new approach is "soft" instead of "hard".

The issue of data migrations is really where I got uncomfortable with this whole thing; Nova moved very quickly to adopt expand/contract, but it was a lot harder to find concrete plans for how they are going to do the database API part of it.   I originally thought that perhaps they were going to run two versions of the app at the same time and perhaps put the "old" version of the API into some kind of read only mode, but apparently they are really going to try keeping their data model such that it talks to both versions of the schema at once.   So I'm with you, that writing a data API that talks to both versions of the schema at once is very undesirable.  This spec isn't proposing that, it's just proposing that *something* has to be worked out subsequent to this spec.   

Let's consider that there's more than one way to do this, and different ways to either reduce the downtime for an upgrade or eliminate it.   For example, if you did your data model in the entirely traditional way, that is, it only knows about the new schema, even maintaining that approach, breaking up the migrations into "expand" and "contract" means that the "expand" operation could be run while the app keeps running on the old version at least; when your new code comes online, then somehow the new data would have to get there as well, which could just as well be in an "expand offline" step - it's just in this version, we aren't getting a no-downtime migration.

Another way might be that you write your new feature into the code, but that new feature doesn't turn itself on at all until some configurational switch is hit.  Prior to that, the old version of the feature, simultaneously present in the codebase, possibly modified so that it knows how to persist data into the new columns as well (e.g. the messy version), but entirely separate from the new version, continues to run, until all the data is migrated (by whatever means that is).   Then the operator restarts the application which at startup time detects, probably by checking some configurational data in the database, that the new feature is "ready" and the app switches to use that code with the enhanced behaviors.

The notion of the "contract" script being where the data migration is fine also, I don't think Nova's doing that.  I think they are requiring that data is always migrated within the model layer because they have a lot of anxiety about large monolithic data migration operations causing downtime.  I'm not a huge fan of that approach but it might be the best way, I'm not sure.

Overall I don't have great answers to this part, but I can say that when you ask how often you'd be running detection of when we're ready to do the "new" thing", I think it's safe to say at application startup time
is all that's needed - I would imagine a routine just runs at service start time that sets up which versions of the API will run based on looking at some fixed configurational data, likely in the database.  I definitely don't recommend an "optimistic" system that just hits the schema and tries to accommodate a SQL error; retrying on errors is a messy affair and the job of classifying errors on all backends is very difficult (we provide this feature in oslo.db, but I like to rely on that system as little as possible).

Requiring that the app be restarted at some point is not a big deal.  I think it's preferable that in a multinode environment, an operator can restart services on a piecemeal basis and the whole thing stays up and running otherwise; in Nova they hope to leverage the RPC service layer to smooth some of this over and I understand Neutron has something similar happening, though it's not the full blown versionedobjects as of yet.

As far as the expand/contract proposal here, my primary motivation is to lay out clearly how I think we should be doing expand/contract at a schema migration level, so that if/when Neutron and other projects seek to move to OSM partially or fully, this system is in place.'}, {'account_id': 9656, 'date': '2015-06-22 10:40:05.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

@Kevin,

> If I understand this proposal correctly, I have to rewrite the code so that it works with either version of the schema. Additionally, it has to also work with a mix of the old and new schema (i.e. after expansion scripts are applied but before contraction scripts).

Yes.

> So I will need logic in the model that detects the presence of the old column; and, as long as it's present, rely on and update that instead of the new table. Additionally, all of the new features that rely on this table basically have to detect whether or not it is present and disable themselves while the column is missing.

No. If a new column/table is present, you move the data there. After that, new column/table beats the old one.

> Then the migration of the data from the old column to the new table will take place in the contraction script that drops the old column.

Actually, neutron itself should eventually migrate data into new columns/tables. If not, contraction step should fail, and there should be a separate command to enforce the data migration before proceeding (essentially, a series of read-update calls to the object abstraction. 

> If so, I have another question. How often should I be running detection for the presence of the old schema in my application logic? The logic in the model can't know until a query is issued to the DB, at which point an exception will be thrown on a missing column or table. Should we put a special decorator somewhere high up in the stack that catches schema errors that triggers all models to query the underlying DB to determine which schema to use?

The idea would be to hide all those compat details under an object interface similar (or even identical) to oslo.versionedobjects. Then your Network object would just access rbac objects, which would in turn return rbac specific exception (like RBACRuleNotFound) if there are no relevant objects (and/or table is not present), and then you rely on .shared field.

Do you suggest significant performance drop due to this? Or is your concern more about code cleanliness and proper abstractions?

That said, it seems that we may have a lot of work to do in this regard, so maybe rushing with online db migrations right now is not something very wise."}, {'account_id': 7249, 'date': '2015-06-22 11:56:08.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Rushing into db changing is not wise and we need to be careful. I like the approach that Mike described here and it will be great to make it work. But I'm not sure is it OK to freeze people's work because we will be able to fully support online-migration only in M, so in Liberty it is good to have it in test mode."}, {'account_id': 7787, 'date': '2015-06-22 11:56:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

@Ihar, what you suggest seems to be quite different from what Mike was saying. Here is my understanding and response to what I think you are suggesting:

The neutron servers migrate the data. All neutron servers are upgraded to the newer code before any migrations occur so we don't have to worry supporting two versions running concurrently. Otherwise, having the new version migrate the data would completely break any currently running old versions.

>No. If a new column/table is present, you move the data there. After that, new column/table beats the old one.

In my particular RBAC case, a network with shared==False does not have any entry in the RBAC table (that's what makes it not shared). When the new code is checking if a network is shared, how does it know the difference between pre-migration and unshared? It seems like we need an additional mechanism to track which networks have been migrated. Making the shared field nullable would probably work in this case (i.e. if null then it has been migrated).

>if there are no relevant objects (and/or table is not present), and then you rely on .shared field.

No relevant objects just means it's not shared. Once the schema is present, there will be no way to know whether or not to rely on the shared column or the RBAC table without making some kind of adjustment like I suggested above.


>Do you suggest significant performance drop due to this? Or is your concern more about code cleanliness and proper abstractions?

Both. For performance: networks in Neutron are queried for a large amount of the API requests since both ports and subnets belong to a network. Requiring two DB lookups per network lookup would be unacceptable. In this case we can avoid it with careful query writing, but it's going to require a lot of diligence on each migration.

For cleanliness: if neutron is responsible for the migration instead of alembic, we need a lot of funky logic to detect whether or not a network has been migrated yet. (e.g. How the shared expression will end up looking on L294 (https://review.openstack.org/#/c/191707/10/neutron/db/models_v2.py) so the shared status is properly extracted in either pre or post-migration.)

Even when we overcome that, where does all of the migration logic go and what triggers it (e.g. should every lookup check for the new schema and migrate)? Many DB lookups happen outside of a transaction so we would have to wait for a mutating DB call for that network before we can piggy-back a migration. What happens if nobody tries to update the networks, do we also need a long-running task slowly migrating things in the background as well?

Finally, if we have all of this complex data migration intelligence in the app layer, what's the point in having alembic scripts? It seems like with a small step further, the app could also handle the schema manipulations...

I need to think about the various other approaches Mike had suggested because much of our code is too tightly coupled to making direct DB model queries to make the above approach very feasible. If we want to go down that route, we probably need a major refactor to move everything behind a DB API and then ban any direct model queries."}, {'account_id': 7787, 'date': '2015-06-22 11:59:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Also, I'm fine with decomposing my migration script into the expansion/contraction/inception phases as necessary. If I understand Mike's comment correctly, getting them into these phases can be accomplished well before we figure out how we're doing online migration. Just let me know how it should be broken apart."}, {'account_id': 9656, 'date': '2015-06-22 12:40:09.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Yes, mixed version environments are not expected to work (at least for now), since they will struggle for records and the way to update them.

I agree that there is a db API refactoring to be implemented before we can actually start thinking about online migrations. I guess we can walk the following path:

1 implement Mike's 3 phase split; expose phases to db-manage tool;
2 from that point in time, merge all new migration rules in split pieces;
3 while at it, start moving to e.g. oslo.versionedobjects to hide db queries from object consumers;
4 if we are ready for that in M, start exposing live data migration pieces in M for those rules that are in contract tree implemented during Liberty.

That plan is conservative, giving us time to prepare and test the Mike approach without blocking other progress. It would mean that we are ok with merging any existing migration rules as-is until 1 is implemented, and are ok with merging non-additive rules assuming they are split in trees."}, {'account_id': 9656, 'date': '2015-06-22 15:50:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

I started working neutron-db-manage: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/194198/

Note that upgrades are broken, so the patch is merely to check whether direction is as intended.

BTW for some reason, depending on branch labels inside migration scripts (via depends_on=) does not work for me, so I falled back to hardcoded revisions for expand-offline and contract for now. I guess we should somehow make them depend on branches.'}, {'account_id': 11816, 'date': '2015-06-22 16:00:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

> Finally, if we have all of this complex data migration intelligence in the app layer, what's the point in having alembic scripts? It seems like with a small step further, the app could also handle the schema manipulations...

So, I'd say that data migrations and schema migrations are not the same thing.   Reading and writing data from one column or another, one table or another, can be accomplished in a database-agnostic way.  SQLAlchemy is possible because all databases speak SQL with relatively limited differences.   

Schema migrations OTOH are a totally different beast.  In this realm, we get into the issues of column types and constraints, and being able to "automate" that means detection of diffs in schemas in a database-agnostic way, and the "alternatives" section of the specification here goes into why I don't think that's a good idea.

I also don't think that the migration of data itself is going to be generic.   For the version of data migration that occurs as the app runs, I think folks are going to have to build out model classes with both old/new columns on them, and all kinds of other unpleasant things, and their data access methods will have to refer to both explicitly.

Kevin you made another point that perhaps the data is migrated first, *then* the new app is invoked.  That also doesn't work, because as the old version of the app runs, it keeps writing data which undoes the work of the migrations in progress.   

As long as OSM has the requirement that the whole app is at all times completely live, read/write, and scalable, the difficulty of adjusting to schema change is squeezed into the model in an explicit way.'}, {'account_id': 7249, 'date': '2015-06-27 06:17:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 9656, 'date': '2015-06-28 06:12:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 7787, 'date': '2015-06-29 22:33:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

>and the "alternatives" section of the specification here goes into why I don't think that's a good idea.

I didn't mean to stop using alembic, I meant that an app could call alembic to trigger migrations at the appropriate times rather than requiring coordination with the user.

>Kevin you made another point that perhaps the data is migrated first, *then* the new app is invoked. 

I didn't mean to. Here is how I'm envisioning the current workflow:

Old code is running.

Expansion scripts are run which have no impact on the old code.

The old code is stopped and new code runs manipulating the old schema.

Something happens to trigger migration. (unsure about this bit)

After migration is complete, contraction scripts can be invoked.'}, {'account_id': 4393, 'date': '2015-07-01 22:29:18.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

(3 comments)

This makes a lot of sense and I'm glad to see Neutron will be blazing this trail so that we have prior art to fall back on if Nova's approach crashes and burns :)"}, {'account_id': 11816, 'date': '2015-07-02 00:40:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

commit_message:
Propose scripted online schema migrations

This specification discusses the issue of database schema
migrations which may proceed while allowing both the previous
and the updated version of the Neutron database API to run
against that schema at the same time.  This is part of a
larger approach which is to allow a Neutron application
to be upgraded to a new version without incurring downtime
while the database schema is migrated.

Change-Id: Ib27c6eb8c901536f1f30d0911dedd4db13d76e9f

commit_message:
[Reports] Add class for merging data stream

This patch adds class rally.task.processing.utils.GraphZiper
that can process unlimited stream of some values (assume
that is a kind of iteration value) and compose a result list
with expected length.

This is useful for processing data for reports charts, so we
can process arbitrary count of iterations without memory load
and generate effective chart for these iterations.

commit_message:
Add processing of keep_data flag

In case when some partition has keep_data = True
need to elevate flag to file system level and
do not to create new partition table. Do not clean
file system when it has keep_data = True.
There should not be a problem if some raw data
will not be cleaned.

Change-Id: I9e67e4b7f9421d517e360e403fa89ea8ca9f43b8
Implements: blueprint partition-preservation
